<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Test First Fighter Plane: Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The first Iranian-made fighter
plane is expected to be tested during the Defense Week maneuvers
in late September in the southern part of the country, local press
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Ali Shahbazi, an Iranian Brigadier General, was quoted as
saying that the fighter to be tested in the war games code-named
Ra'd-9 (Thunder-9) was manufactured by the Iranian Air Force.
</P>
<P>
The officer didn't elaborate on the type and technical details
of the fighter plane. However, specialists doubt the Iranian Air
Force's capability in producing jet fighters, even military
helicopters.
</P>
<P>
A well-informed source said the first Iranian fighter was
assembled by the Air Force, with its parts made in Indonesia. But
there is no immediate confirmation.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian Air Force, now 15,000 strong, used to have
U.S.-made F-5s and F-14s as its main fighter aircraft before the
Islamic Revolution in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Phone Giant to Join With Italian Phone Firm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- AT&AMP;T, the largest long-distance
phone company in the United States, and the Italian phone company,
Stet S.P.A., announced a broad agreement in Rome Wednesday to
cooperate in Europe and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, negotiated over the last four months, was the
latest move in the industry to form global networks, and is aimed
to better their odds in the emerging global telecommunications
race, according to a report of the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
In Europe, Stet -- short for Societa Finanziaria Telefonica --
will enter a joint venture that AT&AMP;T has with Unisource, a
consortium of phone companies from Sweden, Switzerland and the
Netherlands. In latin America, Stet and AT&AMP;T will form a 50-50
venture to run two operating companies, one specializing in global
links for multinational corporations and the second to provide
links for local phone companies.
</P>
<P>
John R. Walter, AT&AMP;T's president and chief operating officer,
was quoted as saying that for AT&AMP;T in the next five years, "growth
will come from outside the United States." He said that AT&AMP;T
expected Stet's entry into Unisource to increase revenue over
forecast by 30 percent. Revenue in 1997, he said, is expected to
double from 1996, to 400 million U.S. dollars, and to reach 2
billion in five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: Asian, Latin American Success Sets Example </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan today hailed the economic success in Asia and parts of
Latin America, saying it showed the path to accelerated
development lay in better integration with the mainstream of the
world economy.
</P>
<P>
"New and dynamic centers of trade and investment have arisen
in Asia and parts of Latin America, and they are fast becoming the
engines of growth in world output and trade, "Annan said.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking to a high-level panel here sponsored by the
United Nations Economic and Social Council (ECOSOC).
</P>
<P>
The UN secretary-general said while he is encouraged by several
positive economic trends in the developing world, "at the same
time, it is distressing that many developing countries and large
numbers of people in all countries have been excluded from the
benefits of globalization."
</P>
<P>
For many African countries and for the least-developed
countries, "the risk of further marginalization remains
all-too-real".
</P>
<P>
Annan called on the international community to give greater
support to the African countries which are opening up and
liberalizing their economies.
</P>
<P>
African countries are pursuing structural reforms and
adjustment programs, and many have achieved impressive levels of
growth. They need increased and sustained official assistance, and
a comprehensive solution to their external debt burdens, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Above all, to help them to outgrow their dependence on
commodities and aid, their exports must be accorded free access to
world markets," Annan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
