<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodian King Seeks Peaceful Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian King Norodum Sihanouk
sent a letter today from Beijing to his people, calling for
peaceful negotiations to solve the present political crisis in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The bulletin released by the royal palace today quoted the
letter as saying the king was willing to supervise the peace talks
as a mediator, so long as no participants of the talks charged him
with trying to resume political power when there were quarrels.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, the king said "we have to agree to organize a
meeting between those who have power to debate and find a way to
solve all problems under the presidency of the king who is a
neutral referee."
</P>
<P>
"But if (you) appoint me to be president of this big meeting,
(you) should not accuse me of being a power-hungry person who
seeks to take advantage while other are quarrelling," he added.
</P>
<P>
The king also appealed to the two prime ministers, Prince
Norodom Ranariddh and Hung Sen, their parties and troops loyal to
the respective prime ministers to make peace and resume the
cooperative brotherhood and harmonious atmosphere they shared
during 1993 to 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
