<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Auto Makers' Sales Decline in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 3 (xinhua) -- The General Motor, one of the
three big auto makers in the United States, said Wednesday that
its sales fell 13.3 percent last month, following a stellar first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Other auto makers also announced their June sales results, and
together registered a decline, according to a report of the New
York Times today. Ford's sales were down slightly, while Chrysler
Corportion's sales fell 4.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report said, smaller auto makers reported their
sales gains.
</P>
<P>
The weak sales of the big auto makers reflect lackluster demand
for new cars and trucks industrywide, said Wall Street analysts
who are puzzled by the auto industry's slow sales at a time when
economic factors seem so favorable: interest rates are low and
stable, unemployment levels are at record lows, and measurements
show strong consumer confidence and high personal income levels.
</P>
<P>
But some other analysts said that the weak June sales were an
indication that the Federal Reserve was correct in deciding not to
raise interest rates to slow the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
