<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Islamic Painting Distributed Through Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 3 (Xinhua) -- An unidentified Israeli has
distributed through the Internet an insulting anti-Islamic
painting, according to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian press
service based in East Jerusalem, today.
</P>
<P>
The painting depicts a sow, with words "The Prophet Mohammed"
on it, feeding piglings at the breast. Its caption reads: "Thus
do the Palestinian people drink from the prophesies of the Swine
Prophet Muhamad."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the act, the Palestinian Ministry of Planning
and International Cooperation said in a statement that "we
believe this act is part of an organized Zionist campaign against
Islam."
</P>
<P>
It noted that the act "refutes Israeli allegations that it is
an individual act."
</P>
<P>
This was the second insulting anti-Islamic incident in a
week. At the weekend some 20 posters were found pasted on
Palestinian stores in Hebron, showing the Prophet as a pig
writing the Koran.
</P>
<P>
The posters touched off a wave of anti-Israeli violence in the
city and elsewhere this week. A 25-year-old Jewish woman from
Jerusalem, suspected of distributing the posters, was detained.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli authorities condemned the insulting act, but
insisted that it was committed by a woman alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
