<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French PM Reaffirms "Privileged" Ties With Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
today reaffirmed that his Socialist government is "profoundly
attached to a policy of particular, privileged and friendly ties
with Africa."
</P>
<P>
"The government should, with President (Jacques Chirac), see to
it that the bilateral relations between Chad and France continue
to develop," said Jospin after a meeting with visiting Chadian
President Idriss Deby.
</P>
<P>
He also said that France's Africa policy should adapt to "the
problems of the time, and the evolution of the spirits, notably of
the African people."
</P>
<P>
President Deby, who is here for a three-day visit, also met
with President Chirac today.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said this week that
France should reflect deeply on its Africa policy and pay more
attention to developing relations with English-speaking African
countries.
</P>
<P>
France's Africa policy has been greatly shaken by the war in
former Zaire, the recent conflict in the Central African Republic,
and the on-going confrontation in the Congo Republic between
President Pascal Lissouba and former President Denis
Sassou-N'Guesso. 
</P>
</TEXT>
