<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jailed IRA Bombmaker Wins Right to Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Gilbert McNamee, an Irish Republican
Army (IRA) bombmaker responsible for killing four British
cavalrymen, won the right today to appeal against his conviction.
</P>
<P>
McNamee has been imprisoned since 1987 to serve a 25-year
sentence for conspiring to cause a number of explosions, including
the 1982 Hyde Park bomb attack on a ceremonial parade by the
Household Cavalry.
</P>
<P>
The Criminal Cases Review Commission, which was set up earlier
this year, referred McNamee's case back to the appeal court after
doubts were raised about fingerprint evidence that was crucial to
his conviction. McNamee's appeal was rejected in 1991.
</P>
<P>
"Following enquiries into a number of issues, including
scientific evidence, fingerprint evidence and the disclosure of
evidence at the time of the original appeal, the Commission
believes that Mr McNamee's conviction should be reconsidered by
the Court of Appeal," the commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
McNamee was convicted after prosecution lawyers told London's
central criminal court that two of McNamee's fingerprints were
found on adhesive tape found on a cache of bomb-making equipment
found in southern England. Another of his fingerprints was found
on a battery used in the Hyde Park bomb which survived the
explosion.
</P>
<P>
McNamee's defense lawyers had argued that while there were only
two of his fingerprints on the tape, there were many more of
someone else's there.
</P>
<P>
These fingerprints might have got onto the tape quite
innocently when McNamee worked at an electronics factory in
Ireland where rolls of the same type of tape were used, the
lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
If McNamee won his appeal, it will be the latest in a series of
convictions for serious crimes to be overturned. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
