<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gun-battle Follows Monarchy Rally in Tirana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A gun-battle broke out in downtown
Tirana, on Thursday, soon after a rally and a march by supporters
of Albania's self-claimed king Leka, killing at least one person.
</P>
<P>
About 500 supporters of the self-claimed king marched from the
main Skanderbeg Square to the headquarters of the central
electoral commission.
</P>
<P>
Firing broke out as the marchers converged on the election
headquarters. Witnesses said the shooting, which carried on for
about 10 minutes, appeared to be aimed into the air. Police
officers guarding the building housing the election commission
fired back.
</P>
<P>
The incident erupted as Albanians awaited the final results
from Sunday's parliamentary elections which officials hope can
help end months of chaos triggered by high-risk investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
Leka has charged electoral fraud in the elections, which also
included a referendum on returning the monarchy to Albania. He has
insisted that monarchy was supported by the majority of the voters
in the referendum, but the central electoral commission said on
Wednesday about 35.7 percent voted in favour of this and some 64.2
percent against.
</P>
<P>
Leka, who has worked as a businessman in Johannesburg, South
Africa, is the son of an army officer who became Albania's king in
1928.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary election results showed that in Sunday's elections,
the Socialist Party defeated the Democratic Party of President
Sali Berisha. Berisha had already conceded defeat despite a second
round of voting on July 6.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Bashkim Fino denounced action of monarchy
supporters in a TV speech and urged people to keep calm.
</P>
<P>
Also today, Berisha reiterated that he would resign.
</P>
<P>
"I will resign. I know you want a date, but it's very difficult
because there's a process involved," Berisha said at a news
conference. He pledged earlier this year that he would step down
if the rival Socialists won the elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
