<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Saudi Arabia Call for Peace in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Egypt and Saudi Arabia highlighted
the necessity of realizing just and comprehensive peace in
the Middle East at a joint meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
"This peace should be based on commitment to the international
legitimate principles, the implementation of U.N. Security Council
resolutions 242, 338 and 425 and on the land-for-peace principle,"
said a communique issued at the end a meeting of the
Egyptian-Saudi Joint Higher Committee.
</P>
<P>
The 7th meeting of the joint committee opened here this
afternoon to discuss ways to boost bilateral cooperation in
political, economic, tourist, cultural and investment fields, and
to regulate Egypt's labor force in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The communique reiterated their countries' rejection of the
Israeli settlement policy in the occupied Palestinian and Arab
territories, and stressed their refusal of "all Israeli measures
and attempts aiming at Judaizing and annexing the holy city of
Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference with his Saudi counterpart Prince
Saud al-Faisal al-Saud, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said
that Egypt and Saudi Arabia are doing their best to save the peace
talks that collapsed in March after Israel broke ground for a new
Jewish settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi minister pledged to continue utmost efforts to "clear
the atmosphere in the region" that has been soured by the
distribution of offensive anti-Islamic posters in the West Bank
town of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
He denounced the incident, saying that the posters reflect
warped Israeli view of the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi official also blamed Israel for poisoning the
atmosphere ahead of the Middle East and North Africa Economic
Summit scheduled in November in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has decided to boycott the summit due to Israel's
participation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Embarks on New Journey in Peace and Serenity (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- When a new work day arrived
following a five-day public holiday, Hong Kong has embarked on a
new journey in peace and serenity.
</P>
<P>
While it was just past midnight and most of the Hong Kong
residents were fast asleep, the "Three Express Trains" had arrived
at the railway terminal at Kowloon.
</P>
<P>
In the past three and a half decades, the trains have traveled
ceaselessly between China's interior and Hong Kong, carrying fresh
non-staple food including meat, fish, poultry and eggs to supply
the Hong Kong market.
</P>
<P>
At four o'clock am, the double-decked trolley bus, a veteran
public transportation vehicle that has been on wheel in Hong Kong
for almost a century, started its first journey of the day across
the Hong Kong island dotted by skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
Then, fresh vegetables with morning dews appeared at dawn on
large and small vegetables stalls across the city. When it was
nearly six o'clock, Uncle Lee, an elderly newspaper vendor in the
downtown Wan Chai district, loaded all newspapers onto his stall
in a neat order.
</P>
<P>
"I have been selling newspapers here for a dozen years," he
said. "But my business has never been brisker than in recent
several days."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is the world's number one metropolis in terms of
press density, with more than 100 local newspapers, journals and
magazines for a population of some 6.4 million.
</P>
<P>
The commercial districts in the downtown area revived at around
8 a.m. with swarms of commuters scurrying to their work. On the
roadside tea houses, however, senior citizens were seen taking
their breakfast with a bottle of tea in a leisurely and carefree
manner.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wong Tai Sin Temple, the most famous religious site
in Hong Kong had been filled with the fragrance of incense sticks.
</P>
<P>
There are some 1,000 religious sites in Hong Kong, which only
has an area of 1,092 sq km.
</P>
<P>
At ten o'clock this morning, Hong Kong Stock Exchange, one of
the world's eight leading stock markets, re-opened after a
five-day suspension.
</P>
<P>
In the Exchange building in Central, red jackets stared at the
electronic board displaying every change of the Hang Seng Index.
</P>
<P>
Shortly afterward, the index jumped to a record height of
15,363 points, a very good sign for the 350,000 financial
professionals working to keep Hong Kong its current status as an
international financial center.
</P>
<P>
Things that will not change
</P>
<P>
Horse race court at Happy Valley was serene and silent, for the
last race season had ended three weeks before. Last season's race
drew an overall stake of some 90 billion Hong Kong dollars (about
12 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, the horse race will resume again in September as
usual, with only some small changes in its name and insignia that
will fade away the trappings of the 156-year British colonial
rule.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Jockey Club, operator of the horse racing, has
invested more than one billion Hong Kong dollars to upgrade and
renovate its headquarters building, develop a world-class racing
court and add more horse stables.
</P>
<P>
Night life is a major feature of Hong Kong's culture. When the
night falls, numerous night clubs, bars, and discos throughout the
metropolis continue to attract tens of thousands of local
residents and overseas tourists with dazzling neons and melodious
music.
</P>
<P>
"The transition of Hong Kong has been so smooth that people
living here could hardly feel it," a foreign businessman in Hong
Kong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
