<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Least Nine Killed in Karachi Building Cave-in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in Wednesday's
building collapse incident in Karachi, Pakistan's biggest port
city, rose to nine Thursday evening following the recovery of
three more bodies from the debris.
</P>
<P>
Rescue work is going on in full swing at the site of collapse
where debris of some three floors had been removed.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, rescue workers retrieved the bodies of six
ill-fated workers in the four-storeyed building under
construction.
</P>
<P>
Three bodies and nine injured were recovered from the debris on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Eye witnesses said that the number of casualties could have
been less had rescue operation not been ill-managed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Embarks on New Journey in Peace and Serenity (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In June 1987, the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping told a
group of visiting foreigners in Beijing that Hong Kong would
remain unchanged for at least 50 years after its return to China,
for "there is no need for it to change".
</P>
<P>
The Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) have announced
that all the policies and systems that had been proved beneficial
to the economic development of Hong Kong, including the free trade
policy, the monetary and financial system, the shipping operation
and management system, and low tax, would remain intact beyond
1997.
</P>
<P>
This has greatly helped to increase Hong Kong people's
confidence in the prospects of Hong Kong's economy, which has led
to the current stability and prosperity in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
To date, Hong Kong has become the world's largest cargo
container port in terms of handling capacity, and the Kai Tak
International Airport has ranked among the world's busiest
airports.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there are 112 ocean-going vessels entering and
leaving Hong Kong daily on average, and every less than two
minutes a plane takes off from or lands at Kai Tak airport.
</P>
<P>
The city is also building a large and modernized new airport,
which is scheduled to go into operation in April 1998. And its
first-phase construction has almost been completed.
</P>
<P>
Since the signing of the Sino-British Joint Declaration, Hong
Kong economy has kept an average annual growth rate of 5.8
percent, and has been reputed as the world's freest economy for
consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, Hong Kong scored an economic
growth of 6 percent, and all predictors expected an annual growth
rate of more than 6 percent for Hong Kong in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is now the regional bases for over 700 transnational
corporations. The latest confidence survey conducted by the
British, Japanese, American chambers of commerce in Hong Kong
among their member companies showed that more than 95 percent of
the respondents are optimistic about the prospects for long-term
investment in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On the ceremony to mark the establishment of the HKSAR, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin reiterated that the principle of "one
country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong"
with a high degree of autonomy is beneficial to Hong Kong, to the
rest of China and to the whole world, and there is no reason to
change it.
</P>
<P>
Things that have changed
</P>
<P>
However, some things do have changed in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
When local residents wake up in the morning and open their
windows, they no longer catch sight of the Union Jack. Fluttering
in the air are the Five-Star Red Flag, China's national flag, and
the Hong Kong SAR regional flag featuring a blossoming bauhinia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Embarks on New Journey in Peace and Serenity (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Even before the handover ceremony on July 1, trappings of
colonialism had phased out quietly. The Queen's head on coins and
stamps, which had been there for one and a half centuries, were
replaced by the pattern of bauhinia and the skyline of Hong Kong
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Starting from July 1, Hong Kong stamps carrying the Queen's
head or British royal insignia had lost validity, and the old
crown insignia of postal service on the over 800 pillar-boxes
across Hong Kong had been removed to usher in the new insignia --
a phoenix that symbolizes a new birth.
</P>
<P>
The Government House, residence for the British Hong Kong
governors, has turned from a heavily-guarded center of colonial
rule into a commemorative site.
</P>
<P>
Two days after the last Hong Kong Governor Chris Patten bade
farewell to the Government House, a solemn ceremony was held there
by the HKSAR government to present the Grand Bauhinia Medal, the
highest award in the new honors system, to 12 recipients who had
contributed tremendously to the local community.
</P>
<P>
At 9 a.m. today, Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of the HKSAR
and all principal officials of the SAR government reached their
offices for the first day of work for the civil service of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
"We're now the masters of our own destiny," Donald Tsang
Yam-kuen, Financial Secretary of the HKSAR government, said with a
sense of pride.
</P>
<P>
Another distinct sign for change is the Five-Star Red Flag
flying over Tamar, the former site of the British Hong Kong
garrison which was taken over by the troops of the People's
Liberation Army (PLA) Hong Kong Garrison at midnight Monday.
</P>
<P>
The withdrawal of the British military force and the entry of
the PLA troops have been regarded as a significant symbol of
China's resumption of its exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong
after 156 years of British occupation.
</P>
<P>
In peace and serenity, Hong Kong, back to the embrace of its
motherland, is ushering in a brilliant and more splendid future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
