<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Doctors Vote Against Euthanasia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- British doctors today strongly
rejected the change of the law that bars doctors from carrying out
mercy killings or helping dying patients to kill themselves.
</P>
<P>
The doctors attending the annual conference of the British
Medical Association (BMA) in Edinburgh passed the motion after a
lengthy debate.
</P>
<P>
Some doctors described as agonizing the decisions they had
faced when terminally ill patients had appealed to them for help
to end their suffering, and thus called for changes in the law to
legalize mercy killings.
</P>
<P>
Sandy Macara, chairman of the BMA council, said the vote showed
most doctors were against euthanasia.
</P>
<P>
"Others rightly see us saving life, not embracing death. We
should not do anything to betray that trust in our essential vital
function," local reports quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Despite the BMA's solidarity on today's vote, there have been
growing calls in Britain for the legalization of euthanasia and
assisted suicide, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
