<HEADLINE> Lebanon Files Complaint Against Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon filed today a complaint to
an international committee overseeing violations of a cease-fire
in south Lebanon over the Israeli bombardment of a south Lebanese
village Wednesday in which one civilian was wounded.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz said that his ministry
lodged the complaint to David Greenlee, the Cyprus-based chairman
of the five-nation cease-fire monitoring committee over the
Wednesday bombardment of Kfar Tibnit.
</P>
<P>
Boueiz accused Israel of being behind the current escalation
of tensions in south Lebanon, saying that Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu is attempting to distract attentions from his
domestic problems through the escalation.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the state-run Lebanese National News Agency
(LNNA) as saying that the bombardment of inhabited areas in south
Lebanon violated the cease-fire understanding Lebanon and Israel
reached in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire monitoring committee, comprising representatives
from France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the United States, is to
hold a meeting next week to discuss the Lebanese complaint. This
will be the 13th meeting of the committee this year, according to
the LNNA.
</P>
<P>
Tensions escalated in south Lebanon this week following a
series of violent exchanges of fire between the Israeli occupation
forces and their client South Lebanon Army militia on one side and
Lebanese resistance guerrillas on the other.
</P>
<P>
Israeli warplanes carried out this morning an air raid at
suspected target of Lebanese resistance guerrillas in the Saida
area in the western part of south Lebanon. The warplanes fired two
air-to-surface missiles but caused no casualties.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Resistance, the military wing of pro-Iranian
Hezbollah, announced that its fighters launched today attacks at
seven Israeli positions in the Israeli self-carved "buffer zone,"
killing and wounding a number of Israeli soldiers. But the
casualties have not been confirmed by the Israeli side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
