<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Gov't Not to Impose "Irrational Effort" for Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- French Minister of Economy and
Finance Dominique Strauss-Kahn said today that the government
would not impose any "irrational effort" to attain budget criteria
for the European single currency.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the Finance Commission of the French National
Assembly, Strauss-Kahn also said that the government would "give
the means to put public finance in conformity with its valuation
of the Maastricht treaty."
</P>
<P>
But he said that France could not attain the criteria of
cutting its public deficit to 3 percent of its gross domestic
product (GDP) this year, as was required by the 1997 budget law
drafted by the former government of Prime Minister Alain Juppe.
</P>
<P>
"Taking into account all the factors, the objective of limiting
the public deficit to 3 percent of the GDP appears unrealistic,"
he said, adding that the deficit would stand around 3.5 percent of
the GDP, instead of 3 percent, by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
He said that that public deficit stood at 4.2 percent of the
GDP by the end of 1996.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the government would stop the policy of
cutting income taxes adopted by the former government, but would
lower the 20.6 percent added-value tax, or sales tax, in order to
stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
Government spokeswoman Catherine Trautmann said Wednesday that
the government could raise taxes on families and enterprises
earning super-high profits to help improve the budget balance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
