<HEADLINE> Cyprus Denies Alleged Military Support to Kurds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government today denied
a Turkish accusation that Cyprus is providing missiles to the
Kurds who are fighting a separatist war in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides said at his daily
press briefing that both Cyprus and Greek governments have
dismissed claims by Ankara and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash that the two countries offer military support to the
Kurds.
</P>
<P>
"We deny these claims," Christofides said, adding that
"whenever a round of negotiations on Cyprus is due they (the
Turks) escalate these views, slanders and false claims, creating a
climate which is not conducive to effective talks."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman reiterated the Greek Cypriot side's readiness to
attend, with goodwill, the forthcoming U.N.-led direct talks aimed
at achieving a Cyprus solution.
</P>
<P>
The direct negotiations between Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash will take place
from July 9-13, at a rural retreat called Troutbeck, 145
kilometers north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
"President Clerides will attend the negotiations decisively,
backed by his recent talks in Athens and guided by the unanimous
decisions taken by the National Council, the top advisory body to
the president on the Cyprus issue," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Christofides added the governments of Cyprus and Greece
confirmed their close cooperation, noting that during President
Clerides' visit to Athens, earlier this week, the two countries
had "common views on the tactics to be followed."
</P>
<P>
During his three-day stay in Athens, President Clerides
exchanged views with Greek government leaders on Cyprus issue,
prior to the July face-to-face talks near New York.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops occupied its northern
third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
