<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn, Paris Eye Closer Ties Despite Disagreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Germany and France said here today
that the traditional Franco-German axis will not be threatened by
their differences on some key issues such as the single European
currency and the expansion of NATO.
</P>
<P>
After talks with French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine here
this afternoon, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel stressed that
Bonn and Paris are in full agreement in fundamental policies. It
is wrong to speak of "a sputtering of the German-French motor or
even a crisis in the bilateral relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There are no serious problems between Germany and France,"
Kinkel declared. "The privileged relations" between Bonn and Paris
remain of central importance for Europe and a "constant" in the
foreign policies of the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine, who is on the first official foreign visit since the
French Socialist government took office four weeks ago, stressed
that the common goals of the two countries are more important than
their differences in details.
</P>
<P>
He added that such differences also existed earlier between the
two countries but did not effect the bilateral ties adversely.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers today also issued a joint declaration aiming
at improving coordination between the two governments in foreign
policy.
</P>
<P>
It was pledged that the two ministers would make joint foreign
visits in the future and the two foreign ministries would
intensify their efforts to seek common positions on important
bilateral and multilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed to strengthen the exchange of
diplomats and envisaged to establish joint embassies in third
countries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Vedrine held talks with German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl on such issues as the NATO enlargement, the timetable for the
European Union eastward expansion and the planned single European
currency, where France and Germany hold varying positions.
</P>
<P>
On the NATO enlargement, for example, Paris and Bonn have taken
different approaches in the light of a U.S. request to limit the
first wave of members to only three countries: Poland, Hungary and
the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
While France came out in support of more than three candidates
to also include countries like Romania and Slovenia, Germany has
so far stopped short of making firm commitments.
</P>
<P>
On the single European currency, the Euro, Germany has been
insisting on strict adherence to the budgetary and fiscal targets
required for launching the Euro on January 1, 1999, but France
favors a softening of the criteria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
