<HEADLINE> Botswanan President Urges Closer African Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 3 (Xinhua) --Visiting President Ketumile
Masire of Botswana today urged the eastern and southern African
countries to establish closer trade links through cooperation and
exchange of experience.
</P>
<P>
President Masire, who arrived here Monday for a five-day state
visit to Tanzania, made the remarks when he was officially
opening the 21st Dar es Salaam International Trade Fair (DITF).
</P>
<P>
Masire said most countries in the region were underdeveloped,
but could share their experiences from neighbors through trade
fairs and other commercial activities to improve their industrial
products.
</P>
<P>
Masire said the rise of Eastern Asia into an economic bloc was
is by accident but through cooperation and exchange of
experiences among those countries which then shifted into
industralized countries.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the need for the southern and eastern African
countries to promote co-operation and exchange of experience in
agriculture and animal husbandry. "Through improved agriculture,
the lot of the people in the region will improve their living
standard as most people in this area live in the rural areas
depending on agriculture which now needs to be overhauled,"
Masire said.
</P>
<P>
Masire and Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa agreed to set up
a joint commission as a way to strengthen the relations between
Tanzania and Botswana in the areas of agriculture and trade.
</P>
<P>
The 21st DITF, an annual event, has attracted 13 foreign
countries. They are Britain, Kenya, France, South Africa, Iran,
China, Norway, Zambia, Syria, Pakistan, Uganda, Japan and
Austria, and over 500 local exhibitors. 
</P>
