<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Breastfeeding Supported in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Despite the dangers posed by the
AIDS, breastfeeding is still supported by the government in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"Currently available information on the risk of HIV
transmission through breast milk has concluded that there is no
need to change policy based on the 1992 World Health Organization
(WHO) and UNICEF consensus on HIV transmission and
breastfeeding,'' said a statement issued today by the Ministry of
Health and Child Welfare.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry recommends the need to provide voluntary and
confidential HIV testing and counselling for women who
wish to know their HIV status for them to make informed decisions
on breastfeeding.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, health experts have agonised over whether the
threat of HIV should affect breastfeeding. While transmission to the
baby is possible, bottle feeding has also been found to pose a more
serious hazard.
</P>
<P>
At the current weekly AIDS death rate of 500, Zimbabwe is said
to be losing the breastfeeding campaign due to the pandemic.
The country is projected to have 600,000 orphans by the year 2000,
among them babies needing breastfeeding substitutes,
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 25 to 50 percent of babies who escape HIV
infection at birth are likely to contract it through breast milk.
But despite this frightening reality, experts maintain that
babies fed on mother's milk have fewer illnesses and less
malnutrition than those on other foods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
