<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Wants Council to Endorse Peacekeeping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- U.N. special envoy Mohamed
Sahnoun said today he wanted the Security Council to endorse an
African peacekeeping force for the Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came after the Security Council was briefed on the
recent situation in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Sahnoun said the main conflict
concerned presidential elections and who would manage the
elections.
</P>
<P>
The envoy, who has been negotiating with the warring parties in
Brazzaville, said both sides wanted a peacekeeping force which
could supervise a cease-fire and secure the airport to make sure
weapons would not flow into the country.
</P>
<P>
Sahnoun said a multinational force mainly made up of African
countries would need outside, voluntary financing. "Without the
logistical and financial support necessary to send the force, the
process of peace will collapse," he added.
</P>
<P>
The month-long civil war, which has killed hundreds of people,
began when President Pascal Lissouba tried to arrest his
predecessor Denis Sassou and disarm his private army.
</P>
<P>
A mid-June cease-fire was negotiated by the mediators hours
after France pulled out its soldiers from Brazzaville. But
fighting has resumed. 
</P>
