<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Coup Has Liberian Link, UN Envoy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's ambassador to the United
Nations, Jame Jonah, has alleged that there is a Liberian connection
to the country's May 25 coup, saying that the link is responsible for
the intrasigence of the coup plotters.
</P>
<P>
The core leadership of the Revolutionary United Front rebels, whom
he accused of hijacking the coup from the soldiers who executed it,
were mainly Liberians, the envoy said in New York Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We presumed they are taking orders externally," he said, quoted by
the News Agency of Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
"The accent of the rebel leaders just gives them up completely,"
Jonah said, adding that people who had been involved in the Liberian
civil war knew the people.
</P>
<P>
According to the envoy, the people in Sierra Leone who are resisting
to return power to the toppled civilian government are these in the
leadership, and the military people who made in coup are no longer in
control.
</P>
<P>
The coup, the third in the tiny west African country in five
years, has been pressed by universal condemnation, and African
leaders are unanimous in supporting any efforts, including the use
of force, to reverse it.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional organization, Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS), has decided to settle the crisis by dialogue with the
military junta in two weeks beginning June 26. If negotiations fail,
an embargo and the use of force will follow.
</P>
<P>
The envoy also praised Nigeria's leading role in the effort to
reverse the May 25 coup, saying that "without Nigeria's assistance, I
really do not know that Sierra Leoneans can do to remove this illegal
regime from our country."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria is the main contributor of the ECOWAS peacekeeping force
known as ECOMOG whose troops are reportedly holding some strategic
positions in the Sierra Leonean capital of Freetown, including the
international airport.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria and Sierra Leone, both ECOWAS members with the former
currently taking the chairmanship, have a long relationship, with many
in Nigeria's colonial administration being Sierra Leoneans and many
Nigerians attending the Fourth Bay College in Sierra Leone.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
