<HEADLINE> Sierra Leonean Teachers Deplores May 25 Coup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Teachers in Sierra Leone Wednesday
deplored the effects of the May 25 coup on the country's already
debilitated educational system, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The Sierra Leone Teachers Union said in a statement that the
coup "will not only destabilize the fragile educational system
but will cripple all development prospects as Sierra Leone is
considered as a least developed country worldwide".
</P>
<P>
The statement presented to Colonel Abdul Sesay, the spokesman of
the new military government, regretted that the overthrow of the
elected civilian government "has disrupted the country's education
calendar and caused the flight of hundreds of teachers and school
children to neighboring countries".
</P>
<P>
At least 3,000 primary and secondary school teachers and up to
4,000 school children have left the country since the coup,
immigration officials in Freetown was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
