<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Raids Guerrilla Base in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli military helicopters
launched an air raid at a guerrilla base of a radical Palestinian
militant group in the Syrian-controlled Western Beqaa in southeast
Lebanon at 8:35 p.m. (1735 GMT) tonight.
</P>
<P>
Security sources said that the Israeli choppers fired at
least one air-to-surface missile at the hill of Naemi, wounding
four members of the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command led by Ahmed Jibril.
</P>
<P>
Israeli artillery also bombarded Jabel Rafih, a mountain area
which is often used by Lebanese Muslim guerrillas as a springboard
to launch attacks on the Israeli self-proclaimed "security zone"
in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have escalated in south Lebanon in the past two days
following a series of violent clashes between Israeli occupation
forces and their client South Lebanon Army and Lebanese resistance
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon today filed to the five-nation panel overseeing
violation of ceasefire in south Lebanon a complaint over
Wednesday's Israeli bombardment of south Lebanese villages in
which one civilian was wounded.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from France, Israel, Lebanon, Syria and the
United States, which make up the cease-fire monitoring committee,
is to hold a meeting at the beginning of next week to look into
the Lebanese complaint. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capital of Central Africa Remains Calm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Bangui, the capital of the Central
Africa Republic is calm today as negotiations are continuing between
mutineers and the regular forces, sources monitored here said
today.
</P>
<P>
Under the mediation of former Malian President Amadou Toure,
negotiations took place at the archbishop house in Bangui.
</P>
<P>
Both sides in the conflict have accepted to a ceasefire which
the mediators want to be extended, culminating in a final peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The conflict between the mutineers and the African peace
keepers began on June 20. So far more than 100 people have died
in the conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
