<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lockheed Martin to Acquire Northrop Grumman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) --Lockheed Martin Corp. is buying
Northrop Grumman Corp. in an about 8 billion U.S. dollar deal that
combines two of the U.S. biggest defense contractors.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came today would bring together the nation's
No. one and sixth largest defense contractors. If approved by
federal regulators and stockholders, it would create a new giant
with revenue of 37 billion dollars and 230,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposed deal, Lockheed will take also over
3.3 billion dollars of Northrop's debt.
</P>
<P>
Lockheed Martin is wellknown as the maker of the F-16 Falcon
jet fighter and the Trident missile and Northrop Grumman, for its
B-2 stealth bomber and the MX missile system.
</P>
<P>
The two companies already have collaborated on the Joint Strike
Fighter, the F-22 fighter jet and early warning systems.
</P>
<P>
Combining with the larger Lockheed will no doubt be a help.
Lockheed Martin has been on a roll recently, winning one contract
last year to develop the nation's next space shuttle and landing
another that keeps it in the competition to build the nation's
next light strike-fighter jet for the military services.
</P>
<P>
Northrop Grumman, based in Los Angeles, employs more than
45,000 people and had sales of about 8 billion dollars in 1996.
Lockheed Martin, based in Bethesda, Maryland employs 190,000 and
had annual sales of almost 30 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The deal is expected to be completed by the end of the year,
pending approval from federal regulators and two company's
shareholders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Imports Bring Huge Loss to Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is losing more than 26.1
billion Naira (about 307 million U.S. Dollars) annually as a
result of illegal importation of palm oil, refined oil and
tallow, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
The current glut of these products in the domestic market has led
to the crash of the price of palm oil from 48,000 Naira per ton to
25,000 Naira in the past five years, said Femi Adeyehun, chief
executive of Okitipupa Oil Palm Plc.
</P>
<P>
According to him, an average of 900,000 tons of palm oil are being produced?
annually by all the 10 major producers in the country while an
average of 60,000 tons are imported illegally per month.
</P>
<P>
The illegal imports come from Indonesia, Malaysia and Portugal as
well as some west African countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, four major producers have closed down, while
several others are on the brink of collapse, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our investigations show that the rapid decline in the domestic
price of palm oil is caused by dumping of the product either in the
crude, refined and mixture forms on the Nigerian market," he claimed.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than two million agricultural and allied workers
would soon be laid off if the palm oil importation was not checked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
