<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Prime Minister Starts Visit to Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin started today a three-day visit to Germany to discuss
with German leaders issues including European security and Russian
trade with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with German President Roman Herzog in Berlin
Thursday, both agreed that Europe should not be allowed to break
up into blocks again in the light of the planned enlargement of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), a spokesman of the
German presidency said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the German daily Berliner Zeitung,
Chernomyrdin reiterated Russia's opposition in principle to the
NATO enlargement, saying that the expansion of the western
military alliance had already exert negative influence on the
situation in Europe.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that attempts to include the three Baltic
states into the NATO would further deteriorate the situation.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Chernomyrdin will meet German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
at a symposium organized by the Alfred Herrhausen Foundation of
Germany which will discuss Russia's economic and political future.
</P>
<P>
Before his departure for the German visit, the Russian Prime
Minister reportedly voiced criticism over the anti-dumping duties
imposed by the European Union on Russia's textile and steel pipe
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
