<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-03 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Explosions Rock Turkish Ammunitions Factory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- A series of explosions rocked a
state-owned munitions factory in the city of Kirikkale in central
Turkey today, killing one person and injuring many others
including three policemen.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported that raging
fire engulfed the TNT manufacturing plant and tens of thousands
civilians were evacuated from the neighborhood as a precautionary
step.
</P>
<P>
The first explosion blasted the factory complex owned by the
Machinery and Chemical Industry (MKE) company at 08:50 local time
(05:50 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Subsequent explosions continued in the morning and fire spread
throughout the ammunition manufacturing complex.
</P>
<P>
A crisis committee was set up by Kirikkale Governor Behic
Celik to coordinate efforts to control the spread of the blaze.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned TV reported that fire-extinguishing teams could
not control the fire from the ground, so three helicopters were
rushed to Kirikkale to fight against the flames from the air.
</P>
<P>
Aircraft from the Turkish Aviation Agency and police choppers
also took part in the operation.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the explosions shattered windows of
many nearby buildings and forced around 150,000 civilians to
retreat from the area. Many people were seen fleeing the city.
</P>
<P>
The Kirikkale governor announced closure of the city until
09:00 a.m. (06:00 GMT) Friday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and other leaders rushed to
the city this evening to inspect the explosion site and battle
against fire.
</P>
<P>
Mayor of Kirikkale Cemalettin Akdogan ruled out any possibility
of sabotage, saying the explosions might have resulted from a
technical malfunction or human error. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
