<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jospin Rejects Accusation on Renault Plant Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
today rejected accusation from the Belgian government and some
unions that he had broken his promise to stop Renault close its
Vilvoorde auto assembly plant in Belgium.
</P>
<P>
"At no moment in the electoral campaign, did you hear me say:
If the left wins the elections, Vilvoorde will be re-opened. I
said: the issue will be re-opened, and we have reopened it," said
Jospin during a television interview this evening.
</P>
<P>
The French automaker Renault announced last week that it would
stick to its controversial plan to close its Vilvoorde assembly
plant, which would result in the lay-off of 3,100 workers.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian Prime Minister Jean-Luc Dehaene, whose hometown is
Vilvoorde, accused Jospin of creating illusion by giving false
messages during his legislative campaign.
</P>
<P>
Jospin said that Renault would create a new industrial center
on the site of its former plant in Vilvoorde, which will employ
400 workers, and that the social compensation plan for the workers
by Renault, including providing jobs in French auto plants, is
"exceptional."
</P>
<P>
"The social (compensation) plan is exceptional... It is not
true that things will end as it would be ended if there was not a
new majority in France today," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
