<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Escalated in Brazzaville </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Efforts are continuing to bring
the warring factions in the Republic of Congo to stop clashes as
fighting is escalating in its capital Brazzaville, Radio Cameroon
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Forces of President Pascal Lissouba and the milicians loyal to
former president Sassou Nguesso each blamed the other for the
continuing shelling.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mayor of Brazzaville Bernard Kolelas, who has been
seeking to mediate, said President Lissouba had accepted the
peace plan which was negotiated under the leadership of the
Gabonese President Omar Bongo.
</P>
<P>
France and the United States have also joined effort to push
the belligerents to stop the bloody fighting that has lasted in
the city for almost a month.
</P>
<P>
Latest reports said that the United Nations Security Council
has agreed in principle to send a international intervention
forces to Congo.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. special envoy to the Great Lakes Region, Mohammed
Sahnoun noted today that it is urgent for first contingent to be sent
to Brazzaville. 
</P>
</TEXT>
