<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Serb Report on Karadzic Arrest Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. today denied a Bosnian
Serb TV report that the Stabilization Forces in Bosnia had been
ordered to arrest former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic and
his former army commander Gen. Ratko Mladic.
</P>
<P>
The report was "absolutely and unequivocally false," State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said there had been no change in the orders to the
peacekeeping forces led by the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) on their behavior towards alleged war criminals.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Serb Television quoted unidentified Bosnian Serb
security sources as saying that Karadzic and Mladic were to be
arrested on sight and U.S. and British military units had been
designated to capture them.
</P>
<P>
Denying the report, Burns said,"There has been no change in the
instructions for pertaining to the detaining and arrest of
indicted war criminals."
</P>
<P>
He said the rule remained that if any of those troops encounter
people who they know to be indicted war criminals, they are to
detain them for transfer to civilian authority so they may be
arrested and then turned over to The Hague for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
Karadzic and Mladic were accused of committing war crimes by
the Western powers during the Bosnian civil war in 1992-1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
