<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Surges 100 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial average
surged toward 7,900 on Thursday, as tame unemployment data backs
the outlook of Federal Reserve officials and investors.
</P>
<P>
The Dow rose 100.43 points to 7,895.81 for its first close
above 7,800. The famed blue-chip barometer rose 208.09 for the
holiday-shortened week, and has now gained nearly 1,500 points, or
22.5 percent, on the year.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 374.65 million
shares at the market's early 1 p.m. close as against 526.80
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indexes also moved to new highs, after a Labor
Department report showing that upward pressures on employment
costs -- the leading force behind inflation -- remained mild last
month.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 list jumped 12.89 to 916.92, the NYSE
composite index rose 5.98 at 477.69, and the Nasdaq composite
index rose 12.00 to 1,467.61, with all three setting new highs for
the second straight day.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index rose 4.28 to a
record 634.34
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department report showed that the nation's
unemployment rate rose to 5 percent in June, up from a 24-year low
of 4.8 percent in May. Job creation was slower than expected,
wages rose only modestly, and hours worked declined.
</P>
<P>
Bond prices rallied after the employment report, sending
long-term lending rates to their lowest level since February.
</P>
</TEXT>
