<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African FM: Hong Kong's Return Sets Good </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Liu Yegang  Zhao Yi)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 3 (Xinhua) -- South African Foreign
Minister Alfred Nzo today expressed warm congratulations to the
Chinese government and people on the return of Hong Kong to
China.
</P>
<P>
In a reception held in Pretoria to mark Hong Kong's return,
Nzo told Xinhua that China's policy towards Hong Kong has set up
an important example for the whole world.
</P>
<P>
He said China's "one country, two systems" principle has given
a good example both in promoting international stability and
cooperation and in solving regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Nzo also expressed satisfaction, on behalf of the South
African government, with cooperation between his country and
China over South Africa's institutions in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-South African relations, Nzo quoted President Nelson
Mandela as saying that South Africa will establish full
diplomatic ties with the People's Republic of China at the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
"I hope this will promote cooperation in various way between
the governments and peoples of the two countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Gu Xiner, Director of the Chinese Center for South
African Studies based in Pretoria, Nzo spoke highly of China's
successfully resuming the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong,
and expressed hope that Hong Kong will remain stable and
prosperous.
</P>
<P>
Nzo pointed out that Hong Kong's economy is very important to
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa expects to establish diplomatic relations
by the end of this year and hope to have more cooperation with
China in dealing with international affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
