<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Vows to Clean up Standards in Public Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
today vowed to clean up standards in public life, and turned the
screw on the exposed cash-for-questions scandals which involved
opposition Conservative Party members.
</P>
<P>
Five former Conservative Members of Parliament (MPs) were
censured Thursday in a damning report released by Sir Gordan
Downey, the Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards.
</P>
<P>
"I can't imagine if these were Labor Party members and these
allegations were proven against them, that they would be staying
in the Labor Party," Blair told reporters on a visit to his
Sedgefield constituency in northeast England,
</P>
<P>
The report put new Conservative leader William Hague under
pressure to take action against the five MPs. But Hague's scope
for action is limited because none of those criticized was
re-elected in the May 1 election that ended Conservative Party's
18-year rule, and installed Labor in government.
</P>
<P>
Vowing to take tough measures against scandals, Blair said one
of the reasons the Labor Party won the election was because people
believed "there was a need to clean up standards in public life
and we will do that.
</P>
<P>
"We will put forward a whole range of measures in relation, for
example, to the conduct of MPs and ... to party funding. That's
important because people have a right to know that the MPs they
elect are going to do their jobs in a proper way," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister has already used sweeping new rules,
outlawing anything that could hurt Labour's standing, to sanction
two MPs facing allegations of financial irregularities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
