<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Airport Traffic in First Quarter Grows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The world's airports registered a
five percent growth in passenger traffic while cargo volume soared
by eight percent in the first quarter of 1997, compared with the
same period last year, the latest airport traffic report from the
Geneva-based Airports Council International (ACI) said.
</P>
<P>
The ACI report, containing data from 495 airports worldwide,
said that aircraft movements rose by two percent for the first
three months of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Africa witnessed the highest growth of nine percent in
passenger traffic in the first quarter, followed by Asia-Pacific
and Europe with six percent.
</P>
<P>
Airports in Latin America and Caribbean reported five percent
growth, while North America and Middle East saw more modest
increases of three percent and two percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Airports in Asia-Pacific outshone other regions with 14 percent
growth of cargo volume, followed by the Middle East's nine
percent, North America's eight percent, and Europe's four percent.
</P>
<P>
Cargo handled in airports in Africa and Latin America and
Caribbean remained virtually unchanged with 0.7 percent and 0.5
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
African and European airports saw a five percent growth in aircraft
movements, followed by Latin America and Caribbean with four percent,
Asia-Pacific with three percent and North America with one percent.
</P>
<P>
Aircraft movements at airports in the Middle East were lowered by
one percent.
</P>
<P>
ACI Director of Economics Paul Benhke said "broad-based steady
growth in passenger traffic occurred across all regions for the first
quarter of 1997, showing a strong increase over a similar buoyant
first quarter in 1996."
</P>
<P>
"Part of the increase could be attributed to the early Easter
travel season falling within the first quarter this year," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
