<HEADLINE> Chairmen of Ten More Provisional District Boards Elected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Ten more Hong Kong Provisional
District Boards each elected a chairman at their respective
meetings today, in the wake of the first wave of the legislative
body chief elections.
</P>
<P>
They are as the following:
</P>
<P>
-- Ng Sze-fuk, chairman of Sai Kung Provisional District Board;
</P>
<P>
-- Chan Lau-fong, chairman of Tsuen Wan Provisional District
Board;
</P>
<P>
-- Tai Kuen, chairman of Yuen Long Provisional District Board;
</P>
<P>
-- Tang Kwok-yung, chairman of North Provisional District
Board;
</P>
<P>
-- Chan Bing-woon, chairman of Eastern Provisional District
Board;
</P>
<P>
-- Chan Chit-kwai, chairman of Central and Western Provisional
District Board;
</P>
<P>
-- Tam Kwok-kiu, chairman of Sham Shui Po Provisional District
Board;
</P>
<P>
-- Hau Shui-pui, chairman of Kwun Tong Provisional District
Board;
</P>
<P>
-- Chan Kam-man, chairman of Wong Tai Sin Provisional District
Board;
</P>
<P>
-- and Chow Chun-Fai, chairman of Yau Tsim Mong Provisional
District Board.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, on Thursday, six out of all the 18 Hong Kong
Provisional District Boards each elected a chairman at their
respective meetings. This was the first gathering since the
Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) began its work within Hong
Kong on July 1.
</P>
<P>
Peggy Lam, Lau Wong-fat, Choy Kan-pui, Lam Wai-keung, Cheung
Hok-ming and Mar Yuer-har were elected respectively chairmen of
the Provisional District Boards of Wan Chai, Tuen Myn, Sha Tin,
the Islands, Tai Po and Southern during Thursday elections.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese National People's Congress (NPC) Standing Committee
stated in August 1993 that the last District Boards of the
London-controlled Hong Kong government should end their existence
by June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
the Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) in February this year adopted the
decision to form the new Provisional District Boards of the HKSAR
and that it was up to the government of the HKSAR to take charge
of making due preparations. In June this year, the HKSAR Chief
Executive's Office announced a namelist of the members of the
Provisional District Boards, and said that their term would expire
at the end of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
