<HEADLINE> Anti-Japanese Aggression Memorial Hall Has Eight Million Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Memorial Hall of the War of
Resistance Against Japanese Aggression has received over eight
million visitors since it opened a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
The hall was established in July 1987 at the Lugou Bridge, the
site of the July 7th Incident, which marked the beginning of
China's eight-year struggle against Japanese imperialists in 1937.
</P>
<P>
Exhibits in the hall include a vast array of photos and
materials illustrating the crimes of the Japanese invaders,
according to Yu Yanjun, deputy curator.
</P>
<P>
The hall has hosted some 100,000 visitors from 28 countries and
regions, with the majority from Japan. Young people account for 60
percent of the domestic visitors to date.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the hall has twice been named as an exemplary
education base by the Beijing Municipal government. And it was
recently listed by the Propaganda Department of the Chinese
Communist Party Central Committee as one of the country's 100
outstanding patriotism education bases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
