<HEADLINE> Annan Calls For More Efforts For Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan opened the International Disability Center (IDC) today
and called on the international community for more efforts to
improve the rights and lives of disabled people.
</P>
<P>
On opening the center in the French town of Ferney-Voltaire
near Geneva, Annan said: "More than half a billion men, women and
children, roughly one out of every 10 people on earth, suffer some
mental, physical or sensory impairment, making people with
disabilities one of the world's largest minorities.
</P>
<P>
"In developed and developing countries alike, disabled persons
face discrimination and are found disproportionately among the
poorest strata of society," Annan told those at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Former UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar is the
president of the IDC, which was established by the International
Disability Foundation (IDF).
</P>
<P>
Secretary-General of the IDF, Hans Hoegh, was the Special
Representative of the U.N. Secretary-General for the U.N. Decade
of Disabled Persons, which ended in 1992. The United Nation's
Secretariat's Division for Social Policy and Development will have
regular exchanges of information with the IDF.
</P>
<P>
Annan hoped those ties would be further strengthened. He asked
the international community to keep their pledges in the last
decade, "to prevent disability, to enhance rehabilitation, to
fight against prejudice and to build a world in which every
citizen can participate fully and actively". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
