<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gifts from Interior Areas Attract HK viewers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 8,000 people spectators have
visited a range of displaying gifts presented to the newly-founded
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) in the Hong Kong
Convention and Exhibition Center (CEC) over the past two days.
</P>
<P>
The 32 valuable gifts were from the Chinese Central government
and all 31 interior provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities in China's interior area. Its display was held at
the very venue of the historic Hong Kong handover ceremony held at
midnight Monday and closed this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The gift from the Central People's Government is a huge bronze
sculpture featuring a blooming bauhinia, a symbol used in the
special regional flag and emblem of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
A stream of people flocked to the large exhibition hall on the
fifth floor of the Hong Kong CEC all day long today. In the crowd
inside the hall there were both the elderly and teenagers, and
also some people from overseas.
</P>
<P>
"We can tell the kind attention the central and provincial
governments have shown to Hong Kong and its six million people
from the invaluable gifts they have sent to us," many locals
shared this view after their visit to the show.
</P>
<P>
A senior citizen stood with a walking stick in front of a piece
of red wood carving, entitled the "Bridge of Unity", from the
Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region in south China, and look at and
appreciate it with great interest.
</P>
<P>
"We are both 84 and seldom leave home," his friend named Lam
said. "But we agree that we can't miss this exhibition, for it has
a large collection of priceless gifts from across the motherland,
and it is worth seeing."
</P>
<P>
Piano instructor Kathleen Sunshine Kwan, who was taking notes
from the board beside the exhibits that carries the gifts'
whereabouts, said that both the gifts and their verses of
introduction were real beautiful.
</P>
<P>
"From them I can feel the deep affection the people in the
interior areas cherish for us," she said. "It is a pity that the
display can't last longer."
</P>
<P>
With a video camera in hand, a senior citizen in his 70s walked
around and took photos for all art works. His wife Shum
Hakim-ting said that they had flown in from Canada just to see and
experience Hong Kong's historic return to China.
</P>
<P>
"My husband is fond of taking photos. He wants to have photos
of all these valuable and elegant works of art so that we can
enjoy them after we reach home," the old lady explained.
</P>
<P>
Just an hour before the closing of the exhibition, many people
were still queuing at the entrance of hall to await his turn to
enter.
</P>
<P>
"However, owing to heavy rains, there were not so visitors
Thursday. Nevertheless, more than 5,900 visitors came to visit it
today," a HKCEC staff member said.
</P>
<P>
When the exhibition is over, the Hong Kong SAR government will
move these valuable gifts to an appropriate site, so that they
will open to the public permanently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
