<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Malaysia to Strengthen Economic Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China and Malaysia today
agreed to make greater efforts to promote bilateral economic and
trade relations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides today minuted down the agreement at the end of
the fourth meeting of the China-Malaysia Joint Economic and Trade
Commission (JETC).
</P>
<P>
Chinese Vice Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation
Li Guohua and Malaysian Secretary General of the Ministry of
International Trade and Industries Asmat Kamaludin signed the
minutes of the two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Satisfied with the achievements of the bilateral economic and
trade cooperation since the last JETC meeting in 1994, the two
sides shared the view that there are still great potentials for
further expansion and development of such cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to upgrade the structure of commodities for
exchange and increase the share of value-added and hi-tech
commodities in the exchange.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to strengthen mutual investments and promote
their cooperation in regional and international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia voiced its strong support for China to become a member
of the World Trade Organization as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Congratulating China on its resumption of the exercise of
sovereignty over Hong Kong, Malaysia hoped Hong Kong, after its
return to China, would play a strong role as a bridge in promoting
the Sino-Malaysian economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Sino-Malaysian trade has grown rapidly with
the volume amounting to more than 3.61 billion U.S. dollars in
1996, an increase of 7.8 percent over 1995, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
Mutual investments have also increased significantly with
Malaysia becoming the 10th largest investors in China in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
