<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Overhauls Asset Evaluation Agencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China has disqualified two asset
evaluation agencies and suspended five others in an effort to
standardize the valuation industry, an official of the State
Administration of State Property (SASP) said today.
</P>
<P>
The SASP recently launched an annual check of the 107 asset
evaluation agencies directly under its administration and found
seven of them to be unqualified, said Zhang Jixiang, director of
the SASP's center overseeing asset valuation.
</P>
<P>
Of the seven, Zhongyu Certified Public Accountants and Beijing
Xinhua Certified Public Accountants have been stripped of their
qualifications for asset evaluation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The other five, which include Zhongqing Certified Public
Accountants and Guangda Asset Evaluation Company, have had their
business operations suspended and were ordered to meet the
necessary requirements within a set period of time.
</P>
<P>
China approved and established its first specialized asset
valuation agency in 1990. It currently has more than 3,300 such
agencies and over 55,000 professional valuers.
</P>
<P>
As the number of asset appraising agencies has increased very
rapidly in recent years, some unstandard practices have cropped
up, Zhang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
