<HEADLINE> German Opposition Blocks Tax Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD) today rejected a tax reform bill proposed
by Chancellor Helmut Kohl's centre-right government in the upper
house of parliament, in which it holds the majority.
</P>
<P>
The tax plan passed the lower house a week ago where the ruling
coalition is in majority, so it will now be sent to a mediation
committee comprising representatives from both sides on July 10.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are expected to negotiate a compromise deal.
</P>
<P>
The SPD had previously vowed to block the tax reform package,
describing it as socially unjust and lacking a solid financial
basis.
</P>
<P>
The reform bill planned a net reduction in tax revenues of
about 30 billion marks (17 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Both political groups are believed to be considering raising
indirect taxes, including the value-added tax and the petroleum
tax, so as to make up tax revenue loss.  
</P>
