<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Ratifies Nuclear Test Ban Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government decided to
ratify the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) at a cabinet
meeting Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
The CTBT, which prohibits all nuclear test explosions, was
endorsed by the United Nations General Assembly in September, 1996,
after more than two years of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese diet has passed a bill approving the ratification
of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda said his government
will submit documents of approval to the U.N. on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The treaty must be ratified by 44 nations -- the five declared
nuclear powers and all other nations believed to have nuclear
potential -- before it can take effect.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly hope that India and other countries will join the
CTBT," Ikeda said. "We will take every opportunity to persuade
them to do so."
</P>
<P>
Ikeda is expected to visit India and Pakistan later this
month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
