<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TV Joke Stops Germans in Their Tracks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Airports and travel agencies
throughout Germany have been bombarded with inquiries after a
television joke that Bonn is planning an "exit tax" on every
tourist leaving the country.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Theo Waigel was trying to cut Germany's huge
national debt by forcing tourists to pay 100 dollars per adult and
50 dollars per child each time they left the country on vacation,
the German ARD public television network said in its "Monitor"
public affairs show Thursday evening
</P>
<P>
Later that evening and next morning Germany's airport
ticket-booking counters and travel services were "bombarded" with
telephone calls from puzzled travelers demanding explanations, or
threatening to cancel travel plans, said the German news agency
DPA.
</P>
<P>
The DPA quoted German Travel Bureau Association official Ariane
Alzer as saying: "This will cost us millions in lost revenue.".
</P>
<P>
However, the Cologne-based WDR television, which produced the
"Monitor" show for ARD, apparently remains light-hearted.
</P>
<P>
"It was supposed to be tongue-in-check, an ironical satire," a
WDR spokesman said. "But many Germans apparently just don't
understand that kind of humor."
</P>
<P>
The incident has dramatized Germany's public fears that the
Bonn government will take more unconventional moves to reduce
state debt and tighten its budget in its struggle to meet the
strict requirements specified in the European Union's Maastricht
treaty for joining the planned single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The Bonn government has already been sharply criticized for its
fund-raising moves to revalue the central bank's gold reserves, to
sell state assets, and to raise indirect taxes such as a petrol
tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
