<HEADLINE> Indonesia Denies Asked to Solve Cambodia's Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas today denied that the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) has asked his country and France to help solve
Cambodia's political crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is that if Cambodia requests (such help), the ASEAN
would be ready to give technical assistance to the (Cambodian)
government which will soon be organizing its general elections,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
A foreign news agency has earlier quoted a Thai foreign
ministry official as saying that ASEAN will ask Indonesia and
France to help solve the political crisis in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
But Alatas denied the report and said it is difficult for
Indonesia and France to meddle in Cambodia's internal affairs
because Cambodia is a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of ASEAN countries held an informal
meeting on various regional issues while in Hong Kong for the
handover ceremony earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
"during the meeting, we did touch on developments in Cambodia,"
Alatas said, adding that they decided to offer technical
assistance on preparation for Cambodia's general election.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar are
expected to join ASEAN this month at the regional grouping's
ministerial meeting to be held in Kuala Lumpur.  
