<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dry Weather Becomes More Frequent: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- As Australia faces its worst
drought since 1982-83, researchers warned today that the
dry-weather cycles were becoming more frequent, possibly because
of global warming.
</P>
<P>
The dry conditions in Australia associated with El Nino events
are caused by changes in water temperature and air pressure over
the Pacific and are counter-balanced by heavy rainfall and floods
in South and North America.
</P>
<P>
Kevin Trenberth, an atmospheric scientist from the National
Center for Atmospheric Research in the United States, said today
that in the past 20 years there had been eight El Nino events and
only three La Ninas, the opposite phase of the cycle.
</P>
<P>
Trenberth, who was in Melbourne to attend an international
weather conference, said that the dry conditions could be
aggravated by global warming caused by greenhouse gas emissions.
</P>
<P>
He warned "that now means that drought is something Australia
may have to deal with on a longer term basis."
</P>
<P>
The Bureau of Meteorology also confirmed early this week that
Australia was heading for the most severe El Nino event since
1982-83, and it was likely to last for another 12 months, peaking
in December.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Bureau of Meteorology show that four out of
the 26 major El Nino events in the last 450 years occurred after
1982, when more than six billion US dollars worth of damage was
caused by floods in northern and central America, hurricanes in
the Pacific and drought and fires in Australia, South America and
part of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Trenberth said that the impact of higher temperatures on the
naturally- occurring El Nino events would be to increase the
evaporation of moisture from drought-affected areas and make more
moisture available to areas going through the wet phase of the
cycle.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
