<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Banking transactions were
disrupted in New Delhi, capital of India, today as officers and
employees of banks went on strike in protest against the decision
to set up local area private banks.
</P>
<P>
Bank employees' unions, which have called the one-day strike,
are also demanding removal of what they call an anti-labor clause
in the pension scheme whereby bank employees and officers would
have to forfeit pension for participation in strikes.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Delhi Banks Employees Federation have claimed
that over 1.3 million bank employees all over the country struck
against the government's decision to allow the setting up of local
area banks in rural areas by the private sector and ban
recruitment and compassionate appointments in the public sector
banks.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said that banking transactions in
other big cities of the country were also disrupted due to
strikes.  
