<HEADLINE> Two German Insurance Giants Plan Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Two German insurers, Victoria Holdings
and Hamburg-Mannheimer AG, announced late Thursday night that they
plan to merge into the country's second largest insurer after
Allianz AG.
</P>
<P>
A declaration of intent to link up was signed by management
boards of the two companies Thursday. The move is designed to
improve their position in what is the world's third largest
insurance market after the United States and Japan, company
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The merger plan, which is subject to approval by shareholders
and the German Federal Cartel Office in Berlin, would create a new
entity called Ergo AG with about 40,000 people on its payroll and
a total capital of over 100 billion marks (57 billion U.S.
dollars). 
