<HEADLINE> Cheaper Baht Helps Boost Thailand's Tourism Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Thai tour operators have welcomed
the government's decision to float the baht as it will benefit
their business.
</P>
<P>
The floatation is tantamount to a devaluation of the Thai
currency and will make Thailand a place cheaper to stay in.
</P>
<P>
'The prices for our tour programs will be 25 percent cheaper on
the average if customers pay in U.S. dollars,"' said Tuangsak
Dephasadin, executive of T.T. Tour-East Co., one of the leading
tour operators in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, the costs for Thais traveling abroad will be higher,
as they will have to pay more baht to exchange for foreign
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has designated 1998 and 1999 "the revisit
Thailand years." The Tourism Authority of Thailand hopes its
campaign, 'amazing Thailand', will bring at least 17 million
foreign visitors into the country in the two years and generate a
revenue of around 16 billion U.S. dollars in the said period.
</P>
</TEXT>
