<HEADLINE> Gold Slump Takes Shine of Australian Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A sharp decline in gold stocks in
the wake of the Reserve Bank of Australia's (RBA) decision to
divest two-thirds of its gold reserves sapped the Australian share
market today, prompting across the board falls.
</P>
<P>
Investors dumped gold stocks from the opening bell after gold
price tumbled 7.00 US dollars an ounce overnight.
</P>
<P>
The gold index, which makes up approximately 3.0 percent of the
all ordinaries index, ended 4.1 percent lower today while gold
bullion closed in Sydney at 323.75 US dollars an ounce from 332.60
US dollars last.
</P>
<P>
The leading market indicator, the all ordinaries index,
retreated from a high of 2750.5 to finish 9.5 points down at
2733.4 points.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 338.87 million shares traded worth
755.02 Australian dollars (566.265 million US dollars), with falls
outnumbering rises 718 to 450.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said gold stocks were heavily sold in late afternoon
trade and support from the industrial sector waned as brokers took
"exposed positions."
</P>
<P>
"For many traders in the market it's been a black day, and with
the gold index down four percent, we would expect a lot of
volatility," Morgan's Stockbroking Associate Director Neil Bryan
said.
</P>
<P>
The RBA said it had completed the sales because gold did not
give it enough asset diversification. The move followed sales by
the Belgium, Austrian and South African central banks.
</P>
<P>
"It's a message that yet another central bank thinks gold is
less relevant," Bryan said.
</P>
<P>
Goldfields Ltd posted the biggest losses in the gold index,
losing 12.63 percent, or 24 cents, to close at 1.66 Australian
dollars while Wiluna Mines lost 43 cents, or 10.42 percent.
</P>
<P>
Normandy Mining, which topped turnover with 9.780 million
shares worth 14.345 million Australian dollars (10.75 million US
dollars), fell five cents to close at 1.41 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Plutonic shares fell seven cents to close at 4.105 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Hartley Poynton stock broker Ben Laurence said he did not
believe the gold market had bottomed.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index slipped 11.4 points to 1497.4, while
the all industrials index ended 8.4 points down at 4330.5.
</P>
<P>
The bank sector defied the trend, closing 15.2 points higher at
4952.6.
</P>
<P>
Home-grown investment bank Macquarie made the biggest gains,
surging 60 cents to 12.40 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ closed up 12 cents at 9.87 Australian dollars, Commonwealth
Bank firmed four cents to 16.06 Australian dollars, NAB closed up
five at 19.40 Australian dollars and Westpac added three to 7.91
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the leaders, BHP dipped eight cents to 19.60 Australian
dollars while Rio Tinto finished up three cents at 22.43
Australian dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
