<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Renew Clashes With Israeli Soldiers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Violent clashes between
Palestinian youths and Israeli soldiers continued in Hebron
today, according to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian press
service based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of Palestinian teenagers began their stone-throwing
street battle after Friday prayers.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians threw a home-made hand-grenade and fire bombs
at the heavily-armed soldiers, while shouting anti-Israeli
slogans. The soldiers and border police responded with rubber
bullets and gas grenades.
</P>
<P>
A total of seven Palestinian stone-throwers were wounded, but
no Israelis were hurt.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security men succeeded earlier in the day in
calming down the situation, but later failed to hold back the
angry teenagers after prayers.
</P>
<P>
This morning, the Israeli military authorities sealed off the
largely Palestinian self-rule West Bank city, in an attempt to
put down further violence. Some Palestinians who were not Hebron
residents were barred from entering the city.
</P>
<P>
The week-long wave of violence took place after the insulting
anti-Islamic posters were found outside Palestinian stores. The
posters showed the Muslim Prophet Mohammed as a pig writing the
Koran. The incident aroused furious reactions from Muslims.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, undercover Israeli soldiers infiltrated into a
group of demonstrators as they began hurling stones at the
Jewish settlement around Beit Hadassah. Some teenagers were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army apparently believed that by so doing they
would succeed in putting an end to the daily clashes that have
left dozens of Palestinians and Israeli soldiers wounded.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu today again accused
the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) of being behind the
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a weekly cabinet session, Netanyahu said that
Israel had conveyed serious messages to the PNA over the
anti-Israeli violence in Hebron and Gush Qatif in the Gaza
Strip, and is now waiting to see what response there will be.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel is trying to resume security cooperation
and negotiation with the Palestinians, but the violence is
sabotaging this.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu charged that the PNA is not doing enough to stop
the violence in Hebron and is organizing those demonstrators in
Gush Qatif. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Bourse Index up 39.11 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) index today gained 39.11 points, or 6.3 percent, from
Thursday, to close at 657.09.
</P>
<P>
Some 469 million shares worth 16.5 billion baht (about 589
million U.S. dollars) changed hands.
</P>
<P>
The stock market index rose for three consecutive days since
the Thai central bank on Wednesday abandoned the 13-year-old fixed
exchange mid-rate system and allowed the baht to float under
market forces.
</P>
<P>
The floatation is seen as a de facto devaluation of the baht
and has made Thai shares so cheap that investors simply cannot
resist the temptation to buy, pushing up demand for the shares and
the trading volume.
</P>
<P>
The SET on Thursday gained 49.19 points to close at 617.98
points.  
</P>
