<HEADLINE> Rebel Leader on Peace Talks With Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The rebel Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) has not totally abandoned peace talks with the
Philippine government despite recent military offensives launched
by Manila, a rebel leader said today.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here quoted Ghadzali Jaafar, MILF deputy chief
for political affairs, as saying the MILF suspended the low-level
peace talks "merely to wait for a better atmosphere to resume."
</P>
<P>
In response to the Thursday meeting of the Southern
Philippines' Council for Peace and Development (SPCPD), the MILF
leader also said his group will welcome all initiatives by various
groups for the resumption of its peace negotiations with the
government.
</P>
<P>
The SPCPD met Thursday in Maguindanao province, western
Mindanao, to seek exploratory solutions to the recent conflict
between the military and the MILF, which displaced thousands of
civilians in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The SPCPD meeting decided to continue efforts for the
resumption of the peace negotiations between the MILF and Manila.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome all efforts to normalize the situation," Jaafar
said.
</P>
<P>
But Jaafar said the resumption of the stalled peace
negotiations will all depend on the "sincerity" of the government
in seeking genuine and lasting solutions to the Mindanao problem.
</P>
<P>
The MILF pulled out of the peace talks with the government late
last month after the government troops overran a major MILF camp
in North Cotabato after weeks of fierce fighting.
</P>
<P>
The MILF began peace talks with the government in early January
this year. 
</P>
