<HEADLINE> W. African States Close Down Embassies in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and six other West African
countries have closed down their embassies in Sierra Leone, in
what appeared to be a prelude to the military intervention led by
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria media reported today that the withdrawal of their
diplomats by Ghana, Guinea, Senegal, Benin, Togo and Cote
d'Ivoire started on Wednesday and is expected to be completed
today.
</P>
<P>
Before the massive withdrawal, Nigeria diplomats had already
left Freetown a few weeks ago, Foreign Ministry sources in Abuja
said.
</P>
<P>
The report said the close-down of embassies is following the
recommendation of the foreign ministers of the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS) when they met in Conakry of
Guinea in late June.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Foreign Ministry sources said the withdrawal of
diplomats may be a prelude to the storming of Freetown by the
ECOWAS peace-keeping force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Commander Major-General Victor Malu has said recently
that his troops are ready to flush out the coupists in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
But ECOWAS foreign ministers have agreed in Conakry that
negotiations and economic sanctions will be used to force out the
new military government led by Major Paul Johnny Koromah, before
military intervention is being taken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
