<HEADLINE> Kenya Starts Control Plan for Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan Ministry of Health has
launched a special five-year control program to curb malaria
which has claimed dozens of lives in the eastern African country
since last month.
</P>
<P>
Currently malaria is a leading killer across Kenya due to the
heavy rains as anti-malaria drugs have ran out of stock in most
districts of the country, the East African Standard newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has already provided 42 kits of drugs per
district and will send additional supplies soon, Director of
Medical Services in the ministry James Mwanzia was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he appealed to medical practitioners and leaders to
help educate the public on control measures especially in rural
areas and directed medical personnel in the affected areas to
work with commitment to combat the problem.
</P>
<P>
There is "an upsurge in mosquito density countrywide due to
the cold weather and the situation is compounded by malnutrition
and anemia especially among children who are most affected," he
said in Uasin Gishu District, western Kenya, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He is on a tour of malaria-prone districts there also
including Nandi, Trans Nzoia and Kakamega.
</P>
<P>
Eight people died of malaria in Uasin Gishu last week and up
to 30 malaria victims have died in Nandi following an outbreak of
highland malaria in the area a couple of weeks ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
