<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Upgrade Air Traffic Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- South African air traffic
department will modernize its air traffic services infrastructure
over next four years at the cost of 30 million Rand (6.7 million
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Air Traffic and Navigation Services Company (ATNS) had
entered into a contract with Decca (SA) for the installation and
upgrading of a significant section of the Very High Frequency
(VHF) transmitters and receivers throughout South Africa, ATNS
announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project involves the upgrading of all existing
transmitters and receivers nationwide, the relocation of some of
the existing sites, and the implementation of new sites which may
be required to provide full radio coverage across the country
from about 7,000 feet and above, an ATNS spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said all VHF transmitters and receivers in use in South
Africa required upgrading because of shortcomings in the existing
radio communications coverage.
</P>
<P>
The scheduled duration of the project is four years and work
will begin in the Johannesburg flight information region.
</P>
<P>
"Once the systems have been installed and commissioned, the
air traffic control centers will be well equipped to handle the
ever increasing air traffic flow within South African air space
and the intensified demands of air travel's stringent safety
requirements," the spokesman added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
