<HEADLINE> Mining Industry Urged to Empower Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Mines Minister Swithun
Mombeshora has urged the mining industry to assist the government
in ensuring the economic empowerment of previously disadvantaged
black Zimbabweans is not just window dressing.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day 25th annual general meeting of the
Association of Mine Managers of Zimbabwe in Nyanga of east
Zimbabwe last night, Mombeshora said the racial composition of
various corporate boards within the mining industry reflects the
skewed nature of ownership in favor of white Zimbabweans.
</P>
<P>
He said the government took a dim view of mining companies
which include black Zimbabweans on their boards to appear as
though they were empowering them, yet they deprived them of the
necessary authority.
</P>
<P>
"The empowerment of our people must not be a window dressing
exercise. There are instances where our people are appointed to
chairmanship positions in some of your companies and yet real
power and decision making processes have been totally removed
from the incumbent," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister appealed to large mining firms to consider
assisting small miners or people intending to venture into mining
but lacked resources as part of their contribution toward the
success of the indigenization program.
</P>
<P>
He also urged mining firms to diversify into the production of
non-traditional minerals such as non-metallic minerals.
</P>
<P>
Although Zimbabwe was endowed with a diversity of minerals, he
added, the mining industry was dominated by the production of a
few minerals such as gold, asbestos, coal, nickel, iron, chrome
and platinum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
