<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Declares Its Government Ministers Free from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Iran's judicial chief claimed here
today that his investigation has shown no signs of financial
corruption among the ministers of the outgoing cabinet of
President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
At the Friday congregation, Ayatollah Mohammad Yazdi told
prayers gathered at Tehran University "All of these ministers
have been investigated by my office, there has not been any
case of financial corruption."
</P>
<P>
Article 142 of the Iranian Constitution has made it incumbent
on the Judiciary chief to have a record of the assets of
ministers before and after taking office.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 Iranian members of the parliament (MP) last week
called on Yazdi to implement the article in the Constitution
with some concern about the corruption of high-ranking government
officials.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the corruption has reportedly been a big social
problem due to the tremendous economic hardship in the country
since late 1993. Some banking, customs and government officials
have been prosecuted for crimes of corruption.
</P>
<P>
However, Yazdi said, "The MP's can be sure that I had already
done that duty."
</P>
<P>
The judicial chief said that the law did not make it
mandatory for him to declare the assets of the ministers to the
public.
</P>
<P>
According to the judicial official, the discrepancy in the wealth
accumulated will be reported after consultations with Iran's
Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
"If there is discrepancy, it will be brought to the attention
of the leader, and if he sees it fit, the people will find out
about it," Yazdi added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
