<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Outlines Work of Economic Services Bureau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Secretary for Economic Services
Stephen Ip of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Regions said
here today that economic prospects over the medium remain good.
</P>
<P>
"The government forecast is for a trend Gross Domestic Product
(GDP) growth rate of 5 percent per annum," he added.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing in the Hong Kong Convention and Exhibition
Center, Ip gave a brief introduction on Hong Kong's economic
fundamentals and the work covered by the Economic Services Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has long served as a major trade, financial, tourism
and business center and is widely regarded as one of the most
competitive economies in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Over the past two decades, the average economic growth rate in
real terms was about 7 percent per year. Economic growth has been
led mainly by a surge in the exports of goods, particularly
re-exports, as well as export of services," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ip outlined the work of his Economic Services Bureau, which,
known as Economic Services Branch before July 1, is responsible
for eight areas: civil aviation, shipping and port development,
tourism, telecommunications, postal services, energy, agriculture
and fisheries and meteorological services.
</P>
<P>
On civil aviation, Ip said, "We are committed to maintaining
Hong Kong's position as a center of international and regional
civil aviation. Our target is to ensure that Hong Kong's airport
capacity and air services are sufficient to meet the growth in
demand."
</P>
<P>
On the regulatory side, the Basic Law provides that the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) shall continue the
previous system of civil aviation management in Hong Kong and keep
its own aircraft register, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We and the Civil Aviation Department will ensure that the high
standards of civil aviation management achieved in Hong Kong are
maintained," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the field of port development, the secretary said
that the port is Hong Kong's most important natural resource since
"over 90 percent of our trade, by weight, is handled by the port."
</P>
<P>
Since the opening up of China's economy in the late 1970s, Hong
Kong's container terminals have been serving as the main conduit
for South China's trade with the world. The strong export growth
on the mainland has made Hong Kong the world's busiest container
port for five years in a row, he continued.
</P>
<P>
He reassured that there is no change in Hong Kong's autonomy in
managing the shipping business after July 1, saying "China's
commitment to maintaining Hong Kong's position as a major
international port and maritime center is clearly spelt out in the
Sino-British Joint Declaration and the Basic Law."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
