<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Rises Slightly in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The year-on-year inflation rate in
the Philippines rose slightly to 4.8 percent in June from 4.2
percent in May, the National Statistics Office said today.
</P>
<P>
But the latest inflation level was still lower compared with
the year-ago level of 9.8 percent, according to figures released
by the office.
</P>
<P>
The Autonomous Region of Muslim Mindanao, the southern
Philippines, posted the highest inflation rate at 8.1 percent,
while Eastern Visayas registered the lowest rate at 0.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Inflation for the first semester this year averages 4.6
percent, much lower than the 6.4 percent target for the whole year
under the International Monetary Fund (IMF) program.
</P>
<P>
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said today that the
government is optimistic inflation could be close to the lower end
of the target range of 6.0 to 7.0 percent, if not better.
</P>
<P>
He said the Central Bank will continue watching any possible
pressure on inflation, particularly on the demand side.
</P>
<P>
"We shall continue to look at the core inflation and ensure
that liquidity growth will be significantly more prudent than what
is programmed," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
