<HEADLINE> Turkish Firms Urged to Involve in Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish Union of Chambers and
Commodity Exchanges (TUCCE) has urged local firms to get more
involved in the country's defense projects.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper Daily News today quoted Erol Gemalmaz,
deputy chairman of the TUCCE's Executive Board as saying that the
TUCCE aims to encourage local firms to engage in some of the
defense projects worth 150 billion U.S. dollars that Turkey has
planned for the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Gemalmaz said that a report issued by the TUCCE Thursday
disclosed channels which could be used by industrialists who are
considering investment in the sector.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that currently only 21 percent of the primary
weapons, equipment and spare parts needed by the Turkish Armed
Forces could be turned out by domestic production, and the
remaining is imported from abroad.
</P>
<P>
Retired General Fikret Ulger, who prepared the TUCCE report,
said that among neighboring countries, Turkey ranks the third
after Israel and Russia in allocating funds for defense.
</P>
<P>
Ulger noted that Turkey could provide 75 percent of its total
defense needs by boosting the output of related local firms and
making wise investments in the field based on strategic needs.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, among the 150-billion-dollar defense
project, Turkey needs 750 helicopters, 180 rocket and missile
systems, 150 anti-tank rockets, more than 3,600 tanks and some
frigates, patrol ships, submarines, anti-mine ships, minesweepers,
helicopters and air defense weapon systems in the next 25 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
