<HEADLINE> Stamp Exhibition Marks Return of HK to China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A stamp exhibition was held here
today to mark Hong Kong's return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, sponsored jointly by the Commercial Press Ltd.
(Hong Kong) and the local China Philatelic Association, features
all major commemorative stamps issued in Hong Kong over the past
156 years of the British colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
Some of the stamps bear distinct trappings of British colonial
rule, such as stamps showing the silver wedding for King George VI
and the grand wedding ceremony of Prince Charles.
</P>
<P>
Some others portray local life and traditions in Hong Kong,
ranging from the mass transit railway system to festivities at the
Dragon Boat Festival, Mid-Autumn Festival and the Christmas.
</P>
<P>
Stamps with Kong-related contents issued by the Ministry of
Post and Telecommunications of China, including the latest set of
stamps marking China's resumption of exercise of sovereignty over
Hong Kong, are also on display.
</P>
<P>
Cheung Kam-che, president of the China Philatelic Association,
said that people can learn something about Hong Kong's history and
its transition over the past dozen years from the tiny yet elegant
stamps.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition, held at the Book Center of the Commercial Press
Ltd. in Causeway Bay, opens to the public from 11 a.m. to 9 p.m.
daily. It is expected to last till July 13.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
