<HEADLINE> ROK's LG to Increase Investment in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- LG Industrial Systems of the
Republic of Korea (ROK) will put 100 million U.S. dollars into
China over the next three years for five factories in the Yangtze
River Delta for production, marketing and after-sales service for
LG's elevators and other electro-mechanical goods.
</P>
<P>
Jong Soo Lee, Chairman of the Board of LG, said Thursday in
Shanghai that the company hopes to have 6.5 billion yuan in yearly
sales by the year 2000. The market network will be expanded from
the Yangtze River Delta to south China and the interior of China.
</P>
<P>
LG is sixth in the world in elevator production and has sold
more than 5,000 since it started its first business in Beijing in
1994. Many are being used in commercial buildings in the cities of
Beijing, Shanghai and Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
A factory in Dalian, designed to produce 2,000 elevators a year
and backed by 40 million U.S. dollars from LG, will start
production in August.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said he is confident in China's vast market, and
that more office buildings, hotels, apartments, power plants, and
factories will be built as China's economy grows, creating greater
need for his company's products. He predicts that the annual
demand will grow at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
LG had 800 million yuan in sales in China in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
