<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Largest Prehistoric Fern Habitat Discovered in Yunnan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- World's largest habitat of Cyathea
Spinulosa, a prehistoric fern, and regarded as live botanical
fossil for its co-existence with dinosaurs, was discovered
recently in Longling County, southwest China's Yunnan province.
</P>
<P>
Spinulosa led world's vegetation about 100 million years ago,
and therefore proves valuable to the studies of palaeogeology,
palaeobotany and palaeoclimatology.
</P>
<P>
The size and density of the Spinulosa assemblage is hardly
rivaled in the world, said an official from World Wildlife Fund
(WWF).
</P>
<P>
Densely populating 191.4 hectares in a large natural reserve
called Yiwanshui, meaning "a bowl of water", three species of the
fern have been found to be present in two categories. Yunnan is
known as a kingdom of plants for its diverse flora.
</P>
<P>
Larger than all previously discovered habitats of Spinulosa
combined elsewhere in the country, Yiwanshui is thickly vegetated
with the giant fern four meters tall, which is quite rare in the
world. Some trees even reach a height of ten meters.
</P>
<P>
Strict regulations are being drafted to ensure protection of
the newly-discovered Spinulosa habitat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0133 </DOCNO>
