<HEADLINE> Hefty Wage Bill for Civil Servants Approved in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The government has approved the
allocation of about nine billion Zimbabwe Dollars (818 million
U.S. Dollars) to meet several salary and allowance adjustments
for its 160,000-strong civil servants with effect from July 1.
</P>
<P>
The new packages announced by Public Service, Labor and Social
Welfare Minister Florence Chitauro include payment of the final
20 percent tranche from the job evaluation exercise and a 10
percent across-the-board cost of living adjustment.
</P>
<P>
Transport and housing allowances went up by between 20 and 31
percent on a sliding scale while night duty, on-call, call-out,
stand-by and uniform allowances would be hiked for those in the
health sector.
</P>
<P>
The adjustments approved on Thursday this week were the result
of successful negotiations between representatives of the
government and respective staff associations which were concluded
on Thursday last week.
</P>
<P>
Civil servants went on a nationwide strike last August
demanding higher salaries and better working conditions.
</P>
<P>
The government granted them an across-the-board 20 percent
salary rise and also paid them their annual bonuses, suspended in
1995 because of a crisis in the state's finances.
</P>
<P>
Chitauro, however, said while the increases which would cover
the next 18 months were within funds approved by the government,
it was crucial that such increments be synchronized with ability
to pay considering impact of the expenditure on the overall
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
