<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Sees Moderate Growth in Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Nigeria said in
its latest research report that the country recorded moderate
growth in agriculture last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank's 1996 annual report, the aggregate
index of agricultural production rose by 3.7 percent compared to
3.4 percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
All the sub-sectors contributed to the increase, with crop
production up by 3.6 percent against 3.0 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Last year, all the major staple food items recorded
significant increase except maize and rice whose production
declined by 10.3 percent and 2.5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said that the hectarage under maize and rice
cultivation was reduced, owing largely to inadequacy and late
supply of fertilizers, while farmers switched to planting of
millet, sorghum and groundnut which are less fertilizer
dependent.
</P>
<P>
Cash crop increased by 14.4 percent. Soybean, cotton and
coffee enjoyed appreciable increases while the output of rubber
and shea nut declined.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, the prices of Nigeria's major
agriculture export commodities were generally depressed in the
world market during the year under review.
</P>
<P>
Of the nine commodities monitored, five recorded price rises
while four suffered price drop compared to the 1995 level. The
bank did not say what the commodities are. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
