<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Chart Change Drive to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Will President Fidel Ramos stay in
power after his term ends next June?
</P>
<P>
Most Filipinos, including contenders in the race to succeed the
president, could hardly give a definite answer at the moment
despite Ramos' assurance that he will step down next year.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine constitution, the president serves a
single six-year term and is not allowed to seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said, as campaigns for charter changes are
continuing, no body can predict what will happen at the country's
political stage tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
During the past two years, President Ramos has repeatedly
promised publicly that he plans to retire after his six years in
office are up.
</P>
<P>
But last week, Ramos said that he is finding it hard to resist
the "wide-spread clamor" for him to run for re-election. He was
referring to growing calls to amend the constitution to lift the
limits of his term.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' statement has led to speculations in the country that
the president might seek a second term if charter change drives
would succeed in the end.
</P>
<P>
Amending the charter in the Philippines can be done through
three ways -- a people's initiative, the convening of the Congress
into a constituent assembly, or the calling for a constitutional
convention.
</P>
<P>
At present, campaigners are trying the first option and the
second method to achieve their objective -- to lift term limits of
all elective officials, including the president.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, an organization called "People's
Initiative for Reforms, Modernization and Action" (PIRMA) has been
gathering signatures of voters who favor the lifting of term
limits of elective officials. And last month, PIRMA presented 5.5
million signatures to the Election Commission, calling for a
national referendum on charter changes.
</P>
<P>
The signatures represented 15 percent of about 36 million
registered voters although the constitution requires only 12
percent of voters to set in motion a system of People's Initiative
to amend the charter.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission will decided PIRMA's fate next Friday
after it failed Thursday to hand down its decision on the
controversial petition of the group because its commissioners were
too tight-lipped to reveal their respective opinions during a
tense meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Election Commission's move has provoked a heat debate among
politicians since the country's Supreme Court last month denied
the PIRMA petition.
</P>
<P>
"What the Supreme Court says, goes. It is the final arbiter,
the ultimate interpreter of the law. The Election Commission can
only implement the law, it cannot interpret it," said Senator
Miriam Defensor-Santiago, chairman of the Senate Committee on
Constitutional Amendments.
</P>
<P>
She said that members of the Election Commission risk
impeachment should they insist on deliberating on the PIRMA
petition.
</P>
<P>
But Bernardo Pardo, chairman of the Election Commission
questioned the finality of the Supreme Court ruling on June 10
that there was no enabling law on People's Initiative to amend the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
The six-six vote by the High Tribunal on the petition did not
provide a clear ruling on the absence of an enabling act, he said.
</P>
<P>
Filipinos are now waiting anxiously for another week to see
whether the Election Commission will give President Ramos a chance
to seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
But political analysts said that even if PIRMA's petition will
be rejected by the Election Commission, Ramos' hope for a second
term has not finally been dashed because the House of
Representative dominated by the ruling Lakas-NUCD (National Union
for Christian Democrats) is trying to convene the Congress into a
constitutional assembly.
</P>
<P>
Besides, President Ramos, who distanced himself from charter
change campaigns last year, are now openly supporting
constitutional amendments, though, he said, he does not favor the
lifting of his term limits.
</P>
<P>
With the strong support of President Ramos, the charter change
campaign will not stop until all political parties nominate their
presidential candidates in November, observers said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taxing Informal Sector Unfair: Chiluba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) - President Frederick Chiluba has said
that taxing people in Zambia's informal sector will be grossly
unfair because the government has not given them any support.
</P>
<P>
"The Post" newspaper today quoted Chiluba as saying on
Wednesday that "some of them make a lot of money but it is money
with a lot of risks."
</P>
<P>
"The lack of government support to the informal sector makes
it illegitimate for the government to ask for tax from them. We
have not provided them with any facilities, they can't borrow
from the banks, they lack government support... We haven't
provided them with a roof... It would be grossly unfair to go and
hunt for them," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also said that it will be very difficult to
collect taxes from people in this sector because they are not
organized.
</P>
<P>
In Zambia a large number of people are working in informal
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
