<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Marks 60th Anniversary of July 7 Incidence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and overseas scholars
gathered in Beijing today to mark the 60th anniversary of the July
7th Incident, the opening salvo in the nation's protracted armed
struggle against Japanese invaders.
</P>
<P>
On July 7, 1937, Japanese troops marching on Beijing
encountered stiff resistance from Chinese forces at Lugou Bridge
(Marco Polo Bridge) in the southwestern suburbs of the city.
</P>
<P>
The defeat of the Japanese after an eight-year-long war, in
1945, represented the first full victory over a foreign invader in
contemporary Chinese history. 35 million Chinese died in the
bloody war.
</P>
<P>
Scholars from a dozen countries and regions, including China,
Japan and the United States, attended today's meeting. Some said
that the War of Resistance Against Japan (1937-45) had not only
changed the direction of Chinese history, but also exerted a great
influence on the situations in Asia as well as in the rest of the
world.
</P>
<P>
"Victory over Japan, as well as Hong Kong's return to the
motherland are two great events for the Chinese nation this
century -- they are milestones of the struggle of the Chinese
people to wipe out century-old humiliation," said Bai Jefu, a
Chinese scholar.
</P>
<P>
Hu Sheng, vice chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference and president
of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS), said that the
meeting provided an opportunity for the Chinese people to recount
history, look into the future, and invigorate the country.
</P>
<P>
"While China concentrates on its economic construction, it also
acts as an important force in safeguarding world peace," said Hu,
adding that, "the so-called `China Threat' spread by some
foreigners was groundless."
</P>
<P>
The meeting was sponsored by the CASS in collaboration with
several Beijing-based history-study societies. It heralds the
start of a week-long commemoration of the war, which is expected
to push the nation's patriotic fervor to a new height after the
handover of Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
