<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imported Goods to Cost More in Wake of Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Prices of imported goods will rise
by up to 30 percent in the near future due to the Thai
government's decision to float the baht on Wednesday, retailers
expected.
</P>
<P>
Among items to be affected are computers and their accessories,
and imported alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
Computers and their accessories are expected to rise between 15
to 30 percent after local retailers sell out of their current
stock or can no longer keep prices down.
</P>
<P>
Some computer retailers have already begun working out new
prices, which could be at least 15 percent higher.
</P>
<P>
Some dealers have already stopped distributing equipment due to
the price changes. They are waiting for the baht to stabilize and
to work out a new price range.
</P>
<P>
"The floated baht will hurt our business as our goods are
imported and the prices will go up," said a manager at ASL
(Thailand) Co.
</P>
<P>
Prices of alcoholic drinks, particularly wine, will also jump
after the present stocks run out, import agents and dealers say.
</P>
<P>
Gold prices, which ranged between 4,200 to 4,300 baht per
baht-weight (in Thailand gold weight unit is also called 'baht',
and one baht weight is about 15.2 grams) before the currency baht
was floated on Wednesday, were quoted on Thursday at 4,600 baht.
</P>
<P>
Consumers also worry that they would be badly affected if price
controls on commodity goods are not effectively imposed.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors to be affected include the automotive and
information technology industries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
