<HEADLINE> Repatriation of Congo Refugees Put Off in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The repatriation of some
100,000 Congolese (former Zaire) refugees, who crossed into
Tanzania during the war against Mobotu Sese Seko, is on hold
pending proper preparations, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
A scheduled repatriation on Monday of 300 Congolese refugees
was postponed pending discussions between Dar es Salaam and
Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
Principal Secretary in the Ministry of Home Affairs Bernard
Mchomvu told reporters here on Thursday that arrangements for the
safe return of the refugees being kept in camps in Kasulu
district in Kigoma, western Tanzania, were being made jointly by
Tanzania, Democratic Congo and the U.N. High Commission for
Refugees.
</P>
<P>
"There are procedures which guide the handling of refugees -
you cannot just let them trek home. We have to guarantee their
security," explained Mchomvu.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa's Press Secretary, Patrick Chokala
said, the delay in the repatriation was due to "technical
matters".
</P>
<P>
Chokala also said, "we don't send people home to problems."
</P>
<P>
At present, Tanzania is host to about 400,000 refugees
including 300,00o Burundian Hutus, who fled violence in the
ethnically-divided tiny central African state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
