<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Coastal Defense History Museum Opens to Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Defense History Museum of
Zhenhai Coastal Fort, located close to sites where British
invading forces met Chinese resistance, has opened to the public
in Zhenhai, near Ningbo in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin, also Chairman of the Central
Military Committee, provided a calligraphic rendering of the
museum's name.
</P>
<P>
Qiao Shi, member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and
chairman of the National People's Congress (NPC), as well as Zhang
Zhen and Chi Haotian, vice-chairmen of the Central Military
Committee, also sent calligraphic tributes to the museum.
</P>
<P>
Zhenhai, at the eastern tip of coastal Zhejiang province,
witnessed several military exchanges between defending Chinese
people and forces and Japanese, British and French invading navies.
</P>
<P>
Exhibition halls in the museum, covering 20,000 square meters,
recount the history of those conflicts. On the southern side of
Zhaobao Mountain, Chinese soldiers, assisted by locals, fought a
fierce battle against British invaders.
</P>
<P>
Construction work on the coastal defense museum began in April
1995 and was completed this June. It cost 18 million yuan (2.1
million US dollars), 10.5 million of which was donated by local
institutes and individuals.
</P>
<P>
Ruins of the Zhenhai coastal defense fort near the museum have
recently been listed as a site useful for patriotic education, and
they have been placed under state protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BBC Coming to Tanzania in Full Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The British Broadcasting
Corporation (BBC) plans to enter into partnership with a local
radio station here so that it can broadcast on Frequency
Modulation (FM) wavelength, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
BBC Rebroadcasting Manager for Africa and the Middle East
Michel Lobelle told the press here on Thursday at an occasion to
mark the BBC 40th anniversary that the move aims to increase the
number of BBC listeners in the country.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the BBC Swahili Section's new program plans, he
said BBC has already entered into partnership with Tanzanian
private radio stations -- Radio Free Africa in Mwanza and United
Radio Station in Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Lobelle's announcement came in the wake of reports that BBC
has been allowed to broadcast in Kenya for 24 hours daily on FM
wavelength.
</P>
<P>
The BBC rebroadcasting manager said that BBC could not apply
to have its own channel in Tanzania as it did in Kenya because of
the 1993 Broadcast Act which binds foreign corporations which
want to broadcast in Tanzania to seek partnership with local
stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
