<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wildlife in Southwest China Jungle Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kunming, July 4 (Xinhua) -- There is now more wildlife in the
jungles of Xishuangbanna in southwest China's Yunnan Province,
thanks to local conservation efforts.
</P>
<P>
A recent field study found about 600 wild oxen and 250 Asian
elephants in parts of the southwestern Chinese area, compared with
1984 figures of 170 and 100 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Farmers have even begun to complain that some of the large
animals have destroyed their crops and killed their livestock.
</P>
<P>
Xishuangbanna is the home of 109 rare animal species that are
under state protection, including the wild ox, India tiger, green
peafowl and white-cheeked gibbon.
</P>
<P>
Some 260,000 hectares of forests are now a natural conservation
zone and the local government plans to expand the zone by another
200,000 hectares over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Local wildlife protection officials are working on legislature
that bans hunting in the region, which is inhabited mostly by the
Dai (Thai) ethnic minority.
</P>
<P>
They also set up a fund this year to compensate local people
for losses of crops and livestock destroyed by wild animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
