<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Enact Law to Protect AIDS Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 14 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is set to
outlaw through legislation all forms of discrimination against
people infected with HIV or those with AIDS, the Kenyan Times
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The planned new law will ensure that employers do not base
their hiring of employees on their HIV status and that testing
for HIV will be voluntary with the informed consent of the
employee, a document from the Ministry of Health said.
</P>
<P>
The law will also ensure that insurance companies do not
decline compensation to those insured and were infected after
they bought their insurance papers.
</P>
<P>
Up to one million Kenyans may die of AIDS if the prevention
and control measures are not pursued more aggressively by the
early next century, said the document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
