<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Promises Big Loans for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank will lend China 2.5
to three billion US dollars annually for the three next fiscal
years beginning this month, according to the Bank's resident
mission in China.
</P>
<P>
The loans were approved by the Bank's board of executive
directors and will be used for infrastructure construction,
poverty reduction, environmental protection, and development of
human resources, the mission said.
</P>
<P>
Bank figures show that for fiscal year 1997, which ended on
June 30, the World Bank committed over 2.8 billion US dollars in
loans to 11 Chinese projects.
</P>
<P>
To date the bank has approved 27.97 billion US dollars for 184
projects in China, including nearly 9.2 billion US dollars in
concessional loans extended by the International Development
Association, the Bank cheap loan branch.
</P>
<P>
World Bank-funded projects in China, which resumed its
connection with the Bank in 1980, cover almost all sectors of the
economy but are mostly in agriculture, transportation, energy,
health, education, environmental protection, and industrial
development.
</P>
<P>
A Finance Ministry official said that the World Bank has not
only provided China with relatively cheap funds but has also
provided the advanced management necessary for China's economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Pieter Bottelier, chief of the Bank's China mission, said that
the bank and China have established a "mature and important"
cooperative partnership and that China is one of the best
countries in terms of implementation of Bank-supported projects.
</P>
<P>
To be more efficient, quicker and more tuned-in to China's
needs, the World Bank will reinforce its mission in China in a
program of reorganization in the Bank's headquarters in
Washington, Bottelier noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
