<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Smashes Car Syndicate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian police have detained
four suspects in connection with a syndicate in which motor
vehicles were being cleared by a fake International Police
(Interpol) office in Lusaka' Matero township.
</P>
<P>
While confirming the incident, acting police spokesman Binwell
Chimfwembe said, "our investigations revealed that there were
'Interpol Offices' in Matero compound where vehicles were being
cleared using forged Interpol clearance certificates, motor
vehicle Blue Books (licenses) and driving licenses."
</P>
<P>
The police raided the den in Matero last week in two separate
incidents and arrested the suspects.
</P>
<P>
In the raid, the police uncovered three clearing houses
complete with all official documents including Interpol clearance
certificates and Zambia Revenue Authority documents.
</P>
<P>
Chimfwembe said that some of the 85 vehicles impounded in
Lusaka by Interpol recently believed to have been stolen from
neighboring countries could have been cleared by the same
syndicate.
</P>
<P>
Other items recovered in the raid were passports, national
registration cards, immigration documents, stencils used in the
forgery, official date stamps, needles for making depressions of
blue book numbers and unidentified chemicals.
</P>
<P>
Chimfwembe cautioned the public to verify any Interpol
clearance with the Interpol Office at the police headquarters in
Lusaka as the Interpol Office also processes Zambia Revenue
Authority documents, passports and national registration cards as
well as all kinds of immigration papers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
