<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baht Floating to Deal Blows to Auto, "IT" Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's automotive industry will
be dealt a serious blow after the Thai currency was allowed to
float since Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Both local producers and completely-built-up (CBU) vehicle
importers will feel the pinch. While local-content manufacturers,
which supply 54-80 percent of various assemblers' requirements,
still use imported raw materials, they will have to pay a higher
price because of the weaker baht.
</P>
<P>
As a result, auto sales for this year may drop by 7-8 percent
on last year to 550,000, as against a total vehicle sales target
of 600,000 units, according to Surapong Paisitpatanapong,
spokesman for the Federation of Thai Industries' Automotive
Industry Club.
</P>
<P>
Wasan Pothipimpanon, whose Benz Thonglor group is the largest
Mercedes-Benz dealer in Thailand, said short-term benefits look
good as people will want to buy at the old prices, but the
long-term effect is a price increase of about 100,000 baht for
Mercedes-Benz products.
</P>
<P>
He believed that it may take three or four months for buyers to
accept the new prices.
</P>
<P>
The information technology (IT) industry will be another sector
that will suffer badly, especially for those companies that have
signed large contracts with the government and are committed to
provide equipment that will have to be paid for in US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The entire IT market would see a downturn, and many projects
might have to be canceled as the suppliers could not meet the
higher costs of equipment involved.
</P>
<P>
It is forecast that this year 30 percent of the 'IT' business
in Thailand is to be government contracts, but only 60 percent of
these contracts are likely to be honored.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
