<HEADLINE> Arafat Rejects Israeli Accusation over Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat has rejected Israeli claims that
the PNA is responsible for the continued violence in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with European Union peace envoy Miguel
Moratinos in Gaza on Thursday night, Arafat said he was doing
everything in his power to reduce the level and intensity of
violence and to prevent it from eruption.
</P>
<P>
He maintained that the Israelis were the ones that failed to
honor the signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos conveyed a message from Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu to Arafat, which asked the Palestinian side
to take firm actions to halt the escalation of violence in the
West Bank city Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Before his meeting with Arafat, Moratinos had held talks with
Netanyahu, who strongly held the PNA responsible for the violence
in Hebron and accused Arafat of organizing the riots there.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli premier charged the PNA for violating the Hebron
agreement by not ordering its police forces to stop the
violence. He warned that Israel would not accept a situation in
which violence continued at the same time of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai met with U.S. ambassador to
Israel, Martin Indyk, and Egyptian ambassador there, Mohammed
Bassiouny, Thursday to discuss the current situation. He also
urged the PNA to act firmly to quash the clashes in Hebron to
restore law and order.
</P>
<P>
Violence continued in Hebron Thursday, although at a
relatively lower level.
</P>
<P>
For the first time since the recent wave of violence erupted,
Israeli undercover troops infiltrated the Palestinian
stone-throwers and arrested several of them. At least five
Palestinian stone-throwers were injured by rubber bullets fired
by Israeli soldiers during the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of clashes was sparked last week by the
leaflets, pasted in the Hebron area by a Jerusalem Jewish woman,
Tatiana Susskind, which depicted the Islamic prophet Mohammed as
a pig writing the holy Koran.
</P>
<P>
Susskind, 25, was charged at the Jerusalem District Court
Thursday with offending religious sensibilities and supporting a
terrorist group, the extremist rightist Kach movement.
</P>
<P>
The continued violence reflected the volatile situation caused
by the protracted deadlock in the peace process. The
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks have been frozen since March
when Israel began building the Har Homa settlement in East
Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
