<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Legal Assistance For The Weak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wuhan, July 4 (Xinhua) -- As a sign of further legal
development in China, a 16-year-old boy recently won a case
brought against his father who had beaten him up and forced him
out of the home because he quarelled with his step-mother.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Xiaolong could hardly believe it after his natural father
denied him financial support. But, fortunately he got help free of
charge when a lawyer, sent by the Wuhan University Legal Aid
Center For the Weak, successfully won the case when the court
decided that his father should provide him with a monthly
allowance and a place to live.
</P>
<P>
"We feel quite relieved to see justice done and 'small
patatoes' like Qiu getting legal protection through our help,"
commented Wan Exiang, a law professor and the founder of China's
first non-governmental legal aid society. It provides legal
services for the poor and the weak, especially women, children and
the disabled people.
</P>
<P>
Acting as public defenders, the center's lawyers have handled
216 cases and provided information for thousands of people in need
since it was founded five years ago in Wuhan, capital of Hebei
Province in central China.
</P>
<P>
Professor Wang is not alone in his efforts to introduce a legal
aid system to China, where the concept of the rule of law is
gaining wider acceptance.
</P>
<P>
The national judiciary formally approved the system on a trial
basis in 1994 in certain cities. In November of 1995, China's
first official legal aid office was founded in the southern city
of Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Since then legal aid offices have been set up in over 50 cities
in 17 provinces and autonomous regions, financed by government and
donations from various organizations and individuals.
</P>
<P>
In the past 18 months, legal aid agencies in the big cities of
Guangzhou, Shanghai, Wuhan, Qingdao, and Zhengzhou have sent
public defenders on nearly 1,400 court cases.
</P>
<P>
The practice is set to become an institution. The revised
Chinese criminal procedure and lawyer laws that took effect
earlier this year allow for public defenders in court for those
who are unable to hire a lawyer for themselves.
</P>
<P>
To reinforce this, the Ministry of Justice set up a legal aid
center in May of this year, along with the China Legal Aid
Fund. Minister of Justice Xiao Yang has called for the
establishment of a sound legal aid system as a national network
within the next 15 years. Now institutes of law and university law
schools are being encouraged to participate in the legal aid.
</P>
<P>
Provisional rules on legal assistance say that a lawyer should
perform the public defender service a minimum of once or twice a
year free of charge.
</P>
<P>
"The introduction of the public defender means that it is no
longer just empty talk when we say everyone is equal before the
law," said Ma Kechang, a legal expert at Wuhan University, and "It
means a step further in building up a socialist democracy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0171 </DOCNO>
