<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Economic Empowerment Tips Balance of Global </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Asian economic empowerment has
tipped the balance of the global economic order and would
eventually influence the global political arrangement, Malaysian
Acting Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said today.
</P>
<P>
"Likewise, the cultural re-empowerment of Asia will be a
tremendous force in the shaping of the new global cultural order,"
he said when opening a conference on "Globalization: The
Perceptions, Experiences and Responses of The Religious Traditions
and Cultural Communities in the Asia Pacific Region" in Shah
Alam, about 30 kilometers southwest of here.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Asian would not make any significant contribution
in the making of the new global culture if it remained asleep upon
its "treasure chest of wisdom, science and art, instead of drawing
from its infinitely variegated contents to give birth to new
expression," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader was of the view that globalization has
done Asian countries a good service, especially from an economic
point of view where "the table has been turned, with the dominator
fearing the loss of his domination".
</P>
<P>
"The technology driving the current phase of globalization must
serve as a vehicle that brings about our great re-awakening," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the present wave of globalization and information
revolution has transformed the global scenario while technology
has disrupted patterns and structures of dominance, "be it the
dominance of the North over the South or of the South elites over
their societies".
</P>
<P>
The impact is devastating at both the international and
domestic levels, he said, adding in fact the distinction between
what is domestic and what is foreign has blurred as every village
becomes globalized.
</P>
<P>
He said "globalization has become the buzzword in Europe and
North America as it is set to change their economic fortunes."
</P>
<P>
The Atlantic societies, encompassing Europe and North America,
are experiencing a rude awakening with the flooding of Asian
goods in their markets and their jobs threatened by global
competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since the rise of the Atlantic societies, Asia has had to
adjust itself to external elements and these centuries have
prepared them to accommodate externally induced changes.
</P>
<P>
However, this was not so for the Atlantic societies as "only
their elites were involved in moving and shaking the world, while
the rest of them have remained in their comfortable isolation,
oblivious to what was happening to the rest of the world," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
