<HEADLINE> India to Enhance Struggle Against Economic Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has decided
to activate an economic crime buster as part of the efforts to
enhance struggle against such crimes in the country, a government
official said today.
</P>
<P>
Since the introduction of economic reforms in the country six
years ago, cases of economic crimes have been on the rise. The
government has decided to reconstitute the Economic Intelligence
Council (EIC), formed in 1985, to strengthen coordination and
formulate an integrated strategy to combat economic crimes.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the reconstituted EIC is slated to be held
here on July 22 and the focus of the meeting will be on
inter-agency coordination, as economic crimes usually involve
offenses relating to income-tax, violations of foreign exchange
rules and invoice manipulations.
</P>
<P>
The links between drug related crime and its implications for
narco-terrorism through laundering of black money would also come
under scrutiny, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The main tasks of the new EIC include exploring new measures to
combat economic offenses, formulating a coordinated strategy for
action by various enforcement agencies, advising on amendment of
laws and exploring measures to combat laundering of black money.
</P>
</TEXT>
