<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Conference on Globalization Opened in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Acting Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim said today globalization entailed ethics of
co-existence among believers of different creeds founded upon
tolerance and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
"Peaceful co-existence demands understanding, tolerance and
mutual respect," he said when opening a three-day regional
conference on globalization with the theme "The Perceptions,
Experiences and Responses of the Religious Traditions and Cultural
Communities in the Asia Pacific Region" in Shah Alam, about 30
kilometers southwest of here.
</P>
<P>
He said that while the overwhelming presence of a single
religion in the West has limited its ability to deal with the
"Other", the faithful of various persuasions in Southeast Asia had
learnt to live together harmoniously.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian leader attributed this to the region being a
"fertile land where various strains of spirituality flowered".
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia's multicultural background and historical
experience had nurtured in Malaysians an attitude of guarded
openness towards others which applied well to contemporary
globalization.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said it was somewhat ironical that globalization, which
tends towards uniformity, was happening in an era of pronounced
religious revival, resurgent nationalism and intense assertion of
cultural identity.
</P>
<P>
He said more than any other cultural force, religion would
become the singular most important force resisting the tendency
towards uniformity.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was also of the view that it was understandable that many
Asians were frightened by the prospect of being swamped by a
deluge of images from cultures that had lost a sense of the sacred
and marked by confusion of values, moral decay and the collapse of
family institution.
</P>
<P>
"But so long as we remain circumspect and discriminating,
globalization will be our ally rather than adversary," he said,
adding "We must not be filled with so much fear that we erect a
fortress around us."
</P>
<P>
However, he said, it was advisable to "don a cultural coat of
mail" so as not to be totally defenseless against the onslaught of
the globalizing cultures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
