<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Children More Vulnerable to AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Indian Children are becoming more
and more vulnerable to HIV/AIDS virus with 80 percent of those
catching the killer disease dying within five years, according to
statistics from the country's National AIDS Control Organization
(NACO).
</P>
<P>
Out of the 3,551 AIDS cases reported till May this year in the
country, nearly 150 cases are within the age group of 0-14 years,
accounting for 4.13 percent of the total number of reported cases,
NACO said.
</P>
<P>
The causes of infection in children are either that it passes
from the mother during delivery, the mother may pass on infection
through breast feeding or children may get infected through blood
transfusion, according to findings.
</P>
<P>
As high as 46 percent of the reported cases are infected
through transmission from the mother. Those being infected
through blood transfusion account for 42 percent of the total,
while the remaining may have got infected through breast feeding,
the NACO data said.
</P>
<P>
NACO has taken up a number of programs to create awareness
among the high risk groups and the general population on HIV/AIDS.
It has also taken up specific programs targeting mothers and
children, in addition to supporting workshops, focusing attention
on the vulnerability of women to HIV infection.  
</P>
</TEXT>
