<HEADLINE> Clinton Firm on Inviting Three into NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said today that he foresaw no circumstances under which he would
consent to inviting more than three new countries into the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with European journalists before his trip to
Madrid, Clinton said he would continue to resist French and
Italian campaigns to bring Romania and Slovenia into NATO.
</P>
<P>
But he said, "I don't want America to dictate to Europe."
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the U.S. upholds that the alliance invites
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic in the first wave of
expansion.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to exclude anyone, but I think it is quite
important on principle that we not admit anyone until we're
absolutely sure that their democracy is stable and that they are
militarily capable," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Leaders from the 16-member NATO are to meet in Madrid on
July 8-9 to invite the first group of countries to join. At
least nine NATO countries insist that Romania and Slovenia
should also be invited at the summit.
</P>
<P>
However, Clinton said,"A lot of the members of NATO have told
me they do not favor five, that they understand that politically
it's good to say... Quietly they say we know that you're right,
that this is the right thing to do."
</P>
<P>
Analysts indicated that the U.S. fears that a larger expansion
would cost more and have more difficulties in getting approval of
the Senate. 
</P>
