<HEADLINE> Slovak Foreign Trade Deficit Continues to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Slovakia's foreign trade deficit
soared 38 percent to 29.86 billion koruna (963 million
U.S. dollars) in the first five months of this year over the same
period last year, the State Statistics Bureau (SSB) said.
</P>
<P>
Exports were 119.3 billion koruna (3.84 billion dollars), while
imports stood at 149 billion koruna (about 4.8 billion dollars),
according to the latest figures released by the SSB.
</P>
<P>
The SSB blamed the deficit on the lack of competitiveness of
Slovakian products in Western markets and a huge rise in imports
by various domestic organizations.
</P>
<P>
The foreign trade deficit has become a serious problem for the
Slovak economy. The deficit was 64.5 billion koruna (2.08 billion
dollars) in 1996.
</P>
<P>
On May 1 this year, the government took a series of measures
restricting imports to cut the deficit, including quotas on
non-alcoholic drinks and agricultural and industrial products.
</P>
</TEXT>
