<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Food Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 7 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has launched a food
drive in the whole country to combat any food shortages in the
future, according to Agriculture and Lands Ministry sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the main obstacle to the development of the
country was the on-going war against the Tamil rebels in the North
and the East but parallel to that an economic war was also being
fought.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Organization had forecast a famine in the year
2004. This forecast had been taken as a challenge by Sri Lanka and
launched the food drive to face the famine, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The obstacle for the food drive is the shortage of water. To
overcome the problem, a water conservation program had been
initiated with foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
Under this program, the sources said thousands of small tanks
will be renovated while a large number of agricultural wells will
be sunk in the country.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's paddy production was only 3.5 metric tons per
hectare and if this was increased by another 1.5 metric tons per
hectare, the country would be self-sufficiency in rice.
</P>
<P>
The government had banned the import of some food items such as
chili, potatoes and onions that could be grown locally. While
initially there was a shortage of these commodities, today the
country was self-sufficiency in them, the sources noted.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
