<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Central Bank Sets Reference Exchange Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The central bank of Thailand will
set a reference rate for the baht against the US dollar on a daily
basis after the Thai currency began to float on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi, deputy governor of the Bank of Thailand,
said today that the reference rate is calculated from the average
interbank trading range of baht against major currencies, weighed
against volumes.
</P>
<P>
Setting a reference rate would protect retail buyers of
dollars, including exporters, because they would know the
appropriate exchange rate, said Chaiyawat.
</P>
<P>
The reference rate on Thursday, the first under the managed
float system, was set at 27.383 to the US dollar. It also set the
range for transactions at 26.66-28.90 baht.
</P>
<P>
The Thai market, where traders opted for caution and awaited a
clearer picture of the currency's true value, Thursday opened at
27.50-28.50 baht to the dollar and closed at 28.20-28.70.
</P>
<P>
In offshore markets, the baht reportedly swung sharply, peaking
at 29.50 before closing at 28.25-28-65 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the interbank rate hovered around 21-29 percent as
banks were uncertain of the baht's value and were cautious about
lending. The interfinance rate soared to 25-35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Overnight repurchase rates were 26 percent, compared with a
regular quote of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although the Thai Bankers' Association had set the band width
for trading against the dollar for interbank transactions at 75
satang during the settling-in period, some banks set a wider band,
more than 2.5 baht, for baht/dollar trade as they were unfamiliar
with the new system.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Thailand hopes that the band width would narrow
when the baht's value stabilized, which may take two to three
weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0192 </DOCNO>
