<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian Defense Minister Igor
Dmitriyevich Sergeyev said today that Russia will not provide
weapons to Azerbaijan, nor to Armenia before the Nagorno-Karabakh
conflict is completely resolved.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev told reporters after meeting with Azerbaijani
President Geidar Aliyev that his country will not repair any
technical weapons for the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The defense minister said Russia, Azerbaijan and Armenia will
set up a committee to investigate the illegal sales of Russian
weapons to Armenia.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijan has made several representations to Russia this year
about Russian weapon traffickings to Armenia, but the Russian side
denied the sales.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Aliyev strongly demanded a resolution of
the Nagorno-Karabakh conflict. The Nagorno-Karabakh autonomous
prefecture is in the Azerbaijani territory, but 80 percent of the
residents there are Armenians.
</P>
<P>
The conflict erupted in February 1988 when the Nagorno-Karabakh
claimed to merger into the Armenian Republic. But it was denied by
the Former Soviet government. The ethnic Azerbaijanis clashed with
ethnic Armenians, killing 32 and injuring some 200.
</P>
<P>
the Azerbaijani president arrived here Wednesday, the first to
Russia since he became the president in October 1993. 
</P>
