<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Takes Steps to Deal With Unemployment: Austrian Chancellor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The inclusion of a chapter on jobs
in a new European Union reform treaty is a significant step
forward in dealing with the bloc's jobless problem, Austrian
Chancellor Viktor Klima told the National Council today.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Austria and other members of the EU, a clause
covering employment was included in a EU reform treaty agreed in
Amsterdam on June 17.
</P>
<P>
The clause commits EU governments to greater coordination of
their strategies for employment and allows for small-scale job
creation schemes to be funded from the Union's budget.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the council on the EU's Amsterdam summit in mid June,
Klima said no single measure will be enough to solve the
unemployment problem in the EU, a series of measures will be
needed.
</P>
<P>
Unemployment across the 15-nation Union has remained stubbornly
high over the last year -- the EU-wide jobless rate was 10.8
percent in April, compared with 10.9 percent in April 1996, EU
statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The overall jobless rate for April 1997 remained roughly double
the U.S. rate (4.9 percent in March) and triple Japan's (3.2).
</P>
<P>
An EU summit on employment will be held in Luxembourg this
November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
