<HEADLINE> Nepal Sets Dates for Polio Vaccines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has set
dates for a second immunization program in an effort to eradicate
polio from the country by 2000, local press reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Health Minister Radha Krishna Mainali Thursday declared
December 7 this year and January 18 next year as National
Immunization Days, as decided by all the seven South Asia
countries at the May summit in Male, capital of the Maldives.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, around 3.7 million children under five years
old throughout Nepal will be administered free the polio vaccines,
Mainali said.
</P>
<P>
Polio, a crippling disease which mostly afflicts children, has
been eradicated from most countries through immunization programs.
</P>
<P>
However, the illness still affects a small number of children
in Nepal and few other underdeveloped countries.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government has committed to eradicate polio by 2000
as called upon by the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
The first national immunization program was launched last year,
with some 3.7 million children given free polio drops.
</P>
<P>
Minister Mainali hailed the first program as a success, calling
for people from all walks of life to make the second program
successful as well.  
</P>
</TEXT>
