<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian-Azeri Basic Treaty Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The Russian-Azeri basic treaty of
friendship, cooperation and security was signed by Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and his visiting Azeri counterpart Geidar
Aliyev here today.
</P>
<P>
The 12-page treaty includes measures to maintain security in
the event of a threat to either country and measures to combat
organized and international crime, Itar-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will cooperate in strengthening peace,
promoting disarmament and creating and strengthening international
systems of collective security.
</P>
<P>
They will also make common efforts to promote the settlement of
regional conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Azerbaijan agreed "to develop their relations as
friendly, equal and sovereign states on the basis of trust,
strategic partnership and all-round cooperation."
</P>
<P>
They renounced the mutual use of force or interference in a
country's internal affairs, any type of pressure, including
economic, and undertake to respect each other's territorial
integrity.
</P>
<P>
The treaty condemns separatism in all its manifestations, bans
the establishment and operation on the two countries' territories
of any organizations whose activities are directed against the
sovereignty and independence of the other state.
</P>
<P>
The treaty is valid for 10 years but will be automatically
extended for five years unless one side notifies the other
in advance of its intention to terminate the treaty.
</P>
<P>
Before signing the treaty, the two presidents held a one-to-one
meeting and had talks with other officials in the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Azerbaijan is the only republic in the Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) bordering on Russia which has not yet
signed a border agreement with Moscow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Banks Cut Baht Deposits Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Singapore banks reacted to the
fall in value of the Thai currency by reducing interest rates for
baht deposits, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The OCBC (Overseas Chinese Banking Corporation) Bank led the
way, slashing its three-month fixed deposit rate for the baht by
more than half from 28.75 percent on Tuesday to 10.75 on Thursday,
the Straits Times report said.
</P>
<P>
The decline in the baht was promoted by the central Bank of
Thailand's (BOT) move on Wednesday to float the baht currency in
order to solve its economic woes.
</P>
<P>
The DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Bank and the Overseas
Union Bank (OUB) lowered their three-month rates to 14.32 percent
and 13 percent respectively, from Tuesday's 18.5 percent and
16.125 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rates are indicative as they vary according to the amounts
deposited with the banks, the report explained.
</P>
<P>
The United Overseas Bank (UOB) was the only one of the Big Four
Banks that did not post any interest rates for the baht since its
de facto devaluation. But the bank resumed the exchange of baht
notes for Singapore dollars at its branches, following a one-day
suspension.
</P>
<P>
Since the Thai central bank announced the baht float, the
currency's peg to the US dollar has been uprooted from about 24.5
baht to the US dollar to 29 baht in the offshore markets. By
Thursday, the baht's fall had slowed after a 19 percent plunge on
Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
