<HEADLINE> Soeharto Warns of Future Oil Shortage in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto has
warned that Indonesia could become a net oil importing country at
the turn of the century in the absence of new reserves.
</P>
<P>
"Our oil consumption continues to increase. If we fail to
discover new reserves early in the next century, we will not have
sufficient amount of oil for our needs," the president said
Thursday in Gresik, west Java, according to reports reaching here
today.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto urged the country to increase its utilization of coal
for its domestic energy needs.
</P>
<P>
"Our coal reserves is large, around 31 billion tons. We can
still increase the use of coal," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's coal production is expected to increase to 120
million tons by 2008 from 45 million tons in 1995, according to
government figures.
</P>
<P>
As one member of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, Indonesia now produces around 1.57 million barrels of
crude oil per day.  
</P>
</TEXT>
