<HEADLINE> Chilean Electricity Firms to Invest in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Chile's second biggest
electricity generating company, Chilgener, will invest 250 million
U.S. dollars in Colombia over the next five years as part of a 3.3
billion-dollar expansion drive throughout Latin America.
</P>
<P>
Some 250 million dollars will be spent on buying power stations
to be privatized by the Colombian government and another 500
million dollars will be invested in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
Chile's electricity conglomerate, Chilquinta is also bidding to
expand into Colombia. The company, along with 19 other companies
from Canada, the United States and Spain, have expressed interest
in participating in a public tender to acquire a 48 percent stake
in Colombia's Empresa de Energia de Bogota (EEB) which is being
partially privatised.
</P>
<P>
EEB is being sold off to raise some 1.5 billion dollars to pay
off debts which are nearing maturity, Paulo Orozco, manager of EEB
said today. Shares in EEB's commercial, distribution and
electricity generation arms will be sold on August 27. 
</P>
