<HEADLINE> Combatting Drought in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The people of Shandong Province are
going all out in their struggle with a drought, the most serious
in a century, which has engaged the efforts of more than 17
million laborers.
</P>
<P>
Provincial party and government officials, including Party
Secretary Wu Guanzheng and Governor Li Chunting, have gone to
areas severely hit by the drought and helped with diesel fuel,
machine, power, and water supplies. And the provincial government
has sent seven work groups to supervise the work.
</P>
<P>
Yu Guoping, deputy director of Flood and Drought Control
Headquarters of the provincial government, said that conditions
for dealing with the drought are better this year, with more water
having been stored in water facilities, about 1.2 billion cu m
more than previously.
</P>
<P>
Floodgates of reservoirs have been opened and other facilities
have been used to irrigate arable land and prepare for planting,
Yu said.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.6 million hectares of crops have been affected by the
drought, 100,000 hectares of which have withered plants. And,
farmers can not grow summer crops on 600,000 hectares of
farmland. Not only that, but people and livestock in some areas
have had difficulties getting drinking water.
</P>
<P>
Autumn grain makes up a half of the province's yearly grain
output in this leading grain producer in China. Observers say that
it will be very difficult to reach the goal of having a good
autumn harvest if the current drought continues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
