<HEADLINE> Setting Up Modern Enterprise System in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China's major commercial center
has made considerable progress in a pilot program for a modern
enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 250 enterprises involved in the program showed that
their asset-to-liabilities ratio dropped an average of 2.2
percentage points from 1994 to 1996. The ratio for state-owned
enterprises went down 3.9 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
The assets of the pilot enterprises were up 36.6 percent in the
two-year period to 423.9 billion yuan. Both business and profits
grew steadily during that period.
</P>
<P>
Profits in the mining sector in 1996 were 3.6 times the 1994
figure while those of the transportation and post and
telecommunications sectors were up 97 percent. In the commercial
and financial sectors, profits were up 50 percent for that period.
</P>
<P>
A municipal official says that the experimental program has
also resulted in a new employment method, and that in recent years
about 80 percent of a million displaced workers have been re-hired.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that, because the pilot program covers many
sectors, it is a great help to Shanghai in establishing a market
economy framework. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
