<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Central Bank Dumps Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Australia, the
country's central bank, has sold 167 tons of gold, or two thirds
of its reserves, during the past six months, it was reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The sales, worth 1.8 billion US dollars, were conducted
secretly over the past six months, during which time the gold
price has fallen from around 360 US dollars an ounce to less than
335 US dollars on ounce, the Australian Financial Review reported
today.
</P>
<P>
The move will earn additional income for the bank of about 75
million US dollars, the Sydney Morning Herald said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank made an announcement about the sales in a
statement embargoed until midnight last night.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in the statement that it had reviewed the costs
and benefits of holding gold, and decided that "while there was a
case to hold some gold as a contingency against unforeseen
events," keeping a fifth of its international reserves in gold was
"no longer justified".
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the sale, Treasurer Peter Costello said that
"gold no longer plays a significant role in the international
financial system."
</P>
<P>
Australia's gold industry is likely to regard the sales as a
significant blow, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The decision was immediately slammed by gold producers, which
said the sales would send a "very odd signal" to the gold market.
</P>
<P>
Peter Lalor, managing director of major producer Sons of
Gwalia, said the decision was "extremely disappointing" at a
difficult time of the industry.
</P>
<P>
"The principal reason for this conclusion was that a country in
Australia's position, with large gold reserves in the ground and
high annual production, derives negligible diversification
benefits from holding such a significant proportion of its
international reserves in the form of gold," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Australia produced 273 tons of gold, with analysts
anticipating that the figure would be exceeded in the coming two
years.
</P>
<P>
The gold price hit a four-year low this week, falling to 332 US
dollars an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Gold has traded as high as 850 US dollars an ounce in 1980 and
as low as 285 US dollars five years later, the Melbourne-based
newspaper The Age said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
