<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of today's
major Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Central committees of China's eight non-Communist parties
and the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce have met
over the past few days to discuss Chinese President Jiang Zemin's
three Hong Kong handover speeches made in Hong Kong and Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that President Jiang's speeches had declared
clearly the determination of the Chinese government and people to
stick to the socialist road and reunify the country in line with
the principle of "one country, two systems" conceived by late
Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping and to safeguard regional and world
peace.
</P>
<P>
-- The 26th Session of the Standing Committee of the Eighth
National People's Congress (NPC) concluded yesterday, with laws on
highways and on animal epidemic prevention and a number of
decisions adopted. The meeting was presided over by Qiao Shi,
chairman of the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng met in Beijing yesterday with
Juergen Sarrazin, chairman of the board of directors of the
Dresdner Bank Group of Germany, the first financial institution
from Germany and Europe to open a branch in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The Premier spoke highly of the long-term fruitful cooperation
between China and the German Bank Group and congratulated on the
opening of the Bank's branch in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
-- At the invitation of Chinese President Jiang Zemin, Tuanku
Ja'afar, supreme head of state of Malaysia will pay a state visit
to China from July 8 to 15, the announcement was made in Beijing
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- At the invitation of the Standing Committee of China's
National People's Congress, a delegation of the House of
Representatives of the National Assembly of the Thailand, led by
its First Deputy Speaker Sophon Phetsawang will pay a goodwill
visit to China from July 4 to 8.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The 50-member Provisional Urban Council was sworn in
yesterday morning and re-elected Ronald D B Leung as its chairman.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony conducted by Hong Kong government representative
Louisa Fung, the council members each pledged their loyalty to the
Basic Law and the HKSAR. The members were appointed last week by
the Chief Executive Tung Chee-Hwa of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
-- A Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman has warned that the
Philippine navy's recent activities on the Nansha Islands is
"another serious infringement on China's sovereignty."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Tang Guoqiang, made the remark following the
recent destruction of scientific exploration signs erected several
years ago by China on a reef in the Nansha Islands in the South
China Sea. 
