<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sichuan Disinfects Tainted Soybeans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Sichuan province agricultural
officials have used heat to disinfect the remnants of 10,000 tons
of diseased soybeans which were imported from the United States,
today's China Daily quoted a quarantine official as saying in
Beijing yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Baosen, of the State Administration of Animal and Plant
Quarantine, said the beans, which were imported to China in early
March, were infected with soybean blight, a fungal disease that is
one of the key diseases listed for quarantine in China.
</P>
<P>
The beans, which have been processed for their oil, were
imported by Sichuan Jiali Cereal Corp and Oils Industries Co Ltd
from the United States. The oil-extraction process ensured the oil
was disease-free.
</P>
<P>
The heat-treatment was ordered last month by the Chengdu
Administration of Animal and Plant Quarantine, which had handled
the case since March 7. The judgment also ruled that the soybeans
should not be used as seeds or sold.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Jiali was urged to take special measures to prevent
spilling the soybeans during transportation, loading, restoration
and processing.
</P>
<P>
Packages, soil, and other materials that might be infected also
were to be burnt.
</P>
<P>
The official declined to identify the US company that traded
the beans, and only would say the beans were brought from several
US states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
