<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Machinery's Ink No Longer Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China's machinery industry, the
country's largest industrial sector that also props up the
country's State-owned economy, turned three years of red ink into
black, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The industry, whose production value constitutes one-fourth of
the country's total, has registered net profits in general for the
first time over the past three years although the profit volume
looks small for such a big sector.
</P>
<P>
The industry had been losing money as problems in State-owned
enterprises were projected to continue eroding their business and
internationally strong companies' entrance into China added to the
squeeze on domestic products at home markets.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months of this year, 1.6 billion yuan of net
profits were registered, indicating a 20 percent increase from the
same period last year. Industry officials expect additional
profits in May and June, but statistics will not come until later
this month.
</P>
<P>
However, senior officials from the Ministry of Machine-Building
Industry said there was not enough evidence to show the industry
had reached its low point under intensifying competition from
International giants.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the ministry's department of production and
information statistics said they could not even say the industry
would pass its low point in a short time and then move into
recovery.
</P>
<P>
Profitable plants have increased gains this year thanks to the
so-called Three Major Campaigns the industry has launched to
invigorate product and service quality as well as technology and
product development.
</P>
<P>
But Wang Jianye, director-general of the department, pointed
out the number of enterprises losing money is increasing, and so
are their debts.
</P>
<P>
Orders that major plants have received this year indicate a
decline from last year. As a result, a big portion of the plants'
production capacity will continue to stand idle, and their shares
of the domestic market will remain low.
</P>
<P>
Wang cautioned that the industry will have to continue its
"hard struggle" against floods of imports to survive
internationalization.
</P>
<P>
Other ministry officials said the real danger lies in most
domestic plants' lack of effective means to compete with thriving
foreign companies.
</P>
<P>
Industry officials expect to see initial results in resolving
the competitiveness problem from the three campaigns.
</P>
<P>
By next year, the industry will try to verify good reputations
on brands of 400 major machinery products and 200 major
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To ensure the build-up of technology and better product
development, the industry will complete construction on 300
technical centers at major enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Through the campaigns, which are the central part of the
ministry's work in Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000), the industry
will build a new reputation by the early 21st century, Wang
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Elevator Show Aims to Spark Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- China opened its second
international elevator show in Shanghai yesterday in a bid to
stimulate the industry, today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
More than 190 businesses from 13 countries such as China, the
United States, Germany, Britain and Japan displayed their advanced
products at the show.
</P>
<P>
Among them were many well-known companies including Otis,
Mitsubishi, Schindler, Hitachi, Toshiba, Thyssen, Fujitec and LG.
</P>
<P>
The five-day show at the Shanghai International Exhibition
Center is co-sponsored by the China Elevator Assn, the China
National Tendering Center of Machinery and Electrical Equipment
and the China Council for Promotion of International Trade Beijing
Sub-council.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the show are newcomers such as Adams of the
United States, Hyundai of South Korea and 110 domestic producers.
</P>
<P>
"The show aims to promote economic co-operation and technical
exchanges between overseas and domestic elevator businesses," an
organizer said.
</P>
<P>
Kwon Young Guk, director of LGIS China Headquarters, said,
"Through the show, we hope to have more market shares in China."
</P>
<P>
LG (Lucky Goldstar) started business in China in 1993 and
generated sales of 110 million US dollars last year. Its factory
in Dalian, Liaoning province, cost 65 million US dollars and
produces 2,000 escalators and elevators a year.
</P>
<P>
But the Giant Elevator Company in Zhejiang's Huzhou, one of the
nation's State-owned producers, hopes to seek technical
co-operation with overseas counterparts at the show.
</P>
<P>
"We need overseas advanced technology to upgrade our products
so as to challenge overseas and domestic rivals," said Sun
Guangfeng, the company's sales manager.
</P>
<P>
China turned out 19,400 elevators and escalators between 1980
and 1995, becoming the third-largest producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
"But domestic markets are still challenged by overseas rivals,"
the show organizer said.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, China imported 6,631 elevators and escalators worth
621 million US dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
