<HEADLINE> Sichuan Disinfects Diseased Soybeans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Agricultural officials in Sichuan
Province have burnt the remnants of 10,000 tons of diseased
soybeans which were imported from the United States, reported
today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
Zhang Baosen, an official at the State Administration of animal
and Plant Quarantine said yesterday in Beijing that the beans,
which were imported in early March, were infected with soybean
blight, a fungal disease listed for quarantine in China.
</P>
<P>
It could cause great damage to soybean and other crops, Zhang
said.
</P>
<P>
The beans, which have been processed for their oil, were
imported by Sichuan Jiali Cereal Corp and Oils Industries Co Ltd
from the United States. The oil-extraction process ensured the oil
was disease-free.
</P>
<P>
The heat-treatment was ordered last month by the Chengdu
Administration of animal and Plant Quarantine, which had handled
the case since March 7. The judgement also ruled that the soybeans
should not be used as seeds or sold.
</P>
<P>
Sichuan Jiali was urged to take special measures to prevent
spilling the soybeans during transportation, loading, restoration
and processing.
</P>
<P>
Packages, soil and other material that might be infected also
were to be burnt.
</P>
<P>
The official declined to identify the US company that traded
the beans, and only would say the beans were brought from several
US states.  
</P>
