<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Assists Less Developed Member States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The European Union provided 2,500
billion ECUs (3,250 billion U.S. dollars) to fund environment and
transport projects in less developed EU members in 1996, an EU
annual report said.
</P>
<P>
Four beneficiary EU member states - Spain, Greece, Ireland and
Portugal - got the aid under the Cohesion Fund, set up by the
Maastricht Treaty to improve their environment and transport
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The report on the annual operation of the fund in 1996, adopted
by the European Commission recently, showed that the fund was
equally divided between the environment and transport sectors.
</P>
<P>
Last year took up 16 percent of the total Cohesion Fund of
15,500 billion ECUs (20,150 billion dollars), which covers the
period from 1993 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
The report said the fund, provided in the form of subsidies,
helped create 74,100 new jobs in 1996 and have generated a total
of 243,100 jobs in the four years of operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
