<HEADLINE> Major News items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Australian newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- The Reserve Bank of Australia, the central bank, has shifted
1.9 billion US dollar worth of its assets from gold into the
government securities, selling 167 tons of its 247 tons of gold
reserves in the past six months. The move is likely to sharply
boost the bank's profits.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The federal government confirmed Thursday its willingness to
extend the debate on tax reform to a broadening of the income tax
base, including a crackdown on family trusts, which are growing by
about 50,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- The National Australia Bank's Managing Director Don Argus
has joined the growing band of high-profile businessmen
criticizing the federal government's economic management. Argus
said that Australia's high unemployment, which has remained stuck
above 8 percent since October 1990, was a chronic problem that
could prevent businesses from operating in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Employers are using the federal government's new non-union
employment contracts to strip away penalty rates, free up working
hours and break down union-enforced work practices and
demarcations. The first snapshot of the confidential Australian
Workplace Agreements shows that they have given employers
considerable flexibility.  
</P>
</TEXT>
