<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hingis in Final, Backer Retired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WIMBLEDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- World number one Martina Hingis
and third seed Jana Novotna of Czech Republic sailed smoothly into
the Wimbledon women's singles final after beating their opponents
in straight sets, respectively, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Hingis, the youngest Wimbledon semi-finalist, enjoyed
an unexpected easy win of 6:3 6:2 over 16-year-old Russian Tennis
ace Anna Kournikova, who has beaten Anke Huber and French Open
Champion Iva Majoli over the past few rounds, but failed to create
another upset.
</P>
<P>
Hingis, commonly regarded as a tennis genius, totally dominated
the whole match with her accurated drops and sharp smashes,
forcing Kournanikova make a trail of errors.
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't one of my best performances at this tournament,"
Hingis told reporters. "I tried to keep the ball in the game and
waited for the mistakes...she made more mistakes than winners."
</P>
<P>
Kournikova, nine months younger than her awesome opponent, said
"I did my best, but I have played a lot of tennis in the past week
and was tired. I didn't want to be scared. I just wanted to go for
my shots."
</P>
<P>
During the other women's singles semi-final clash, Novotna,
runner-up in the 1993 Wimbledon Championships, completely trounced
two-times Wimbledon fianlist Sanchez-Vicario in straight sets 6:4
6:2 by staging repeated fierce forehand attacks.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the coming showdown with top seed Hingis due to
play on Saturday, a confideng Novotna said: We will see two
contrasts of style (on Saturday) which will make for good tennis."
</P>
<P>
In the men's events, world number one Pete Sampras, German
veteran Michael Stich, Austrilian doulbes specialist Tood
Woodbridge and French player Cedric Pioline entered the semi-final
stages after beating their opponents.
</P>
<P>
Three-time Wimbledon Champion Boris Backer, who lost 1:6 6:7
1:6 4:6 to top seed Sampras Wednesday afternoon, shocked the
tennis world by announcing that he is to retire from Wimbledon
and the world's other three Grand Slam competition.
</P>
<P>
"That was a my last time at Wimbledon," Backer told Sampras
seconds immediately after his convincing defeat.
</P>
<P>
Explaining his surprise decision, Baker told a press
briefing: "I'm the type of guy who likes to go into a grand slam
tournament with a chance of winning it and I don't feel I have
what it takes to go all the way any more."
</P>
<P>
"I feel very relieved. I feel I have come to the end of the
road with my head held high. I always like to out on top. Right
now I feel I'm on top of the mountain. I can only go down," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Britain's hope of winning Wimbledon trophy was completely
dashed after two British players Tim Henman and Greg Rusedki were
ousted by 1991 Wimbledon Champion Stich and Frenchman
Pioline. Woodbridge, who ousted world number two Michael Chang,
secured his semi-final place after beating 19-year-old German
player Nicolas Kiefer.
</P>
<P>
In the men's semi-finals due to be played on Friday, Sampras
will take on Woodbridge and Stich will play Pioline to fight for a
position in the final showdwon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
