<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Auto Makers Performs Better on U.S. Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- Foreign car makers in the U.S.
showed better performance in their June sales than their American
competitors, according to a number of reports out these days.
</P>
<P>
The Audi of America, Inc. reported U.S. sales of 3,224 for the
month of June, representing a 48.2 percent increase over the same
month last year when sales were 2,176.
</P>
<P>
It was Audi's best June and best first half sales results since
1987. The German company has demonstrated this kind of
year-over-previous-year sales increase for 30 of the last 31
months.
</P>
<P>
So far in 1997, Audi has sold 17,019 automobiles representing a
34 percent increase over the same period last year when the total
was 12,702.
</P>
<P>
The Toyota Motor Corp. reported a 2 percent decline in June
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Mazda Motor Corp. reported on Wednesday that it
reported a 28 percent sales increase in June to 27,062 cars and
trucks. The Mercedes-Benze unit of Germany's Daimler-Benz AG
posted a 15 percent sales increase in the month to a record
8,257 vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, American auto makers showed a weakness in
performance. The General Motors Corp. said its U.S. June sales of
light vehicles plunged 13.5 percent from a year earlier,
reflecting strikes at two assembly plants and an overall softening
in the auto market. GM's double-digit sales decline in June was
among its largest monthly sales declines this year, according to
market analysts.
</P>
<P>
The Chrysler Corp also reported a downward trend for June auto
sales which declined by 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the No. 2 Ford Motor Co. may announce a narrow sales
increase. It may report another increase in light-truck sales,
offset by another decrease in car sales.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- All shares on Europe's major stock
markets ended higher on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
British shares gyrated wildly, plunging at the outset but then
rebounding to record peaks despite the view that Wednesday's
budget would lead to sharply higher interest rates. The FTSE-100
closed at 4,831.7, up 80.3 points.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, share prices rose to drive the IBIS DAX index to
a new all-time high of 3,944.34 in late trade, with dealers'
sights firmly set on breaking the 4,000 level in the coming weeks.
The DAX-30 index closed at 3,887.39, up 32.63 points.
</P>
<P>
French shares closed almost one percent up, on the back of U.S.
employment data which confirmed the bullish mood in the Paris
market. The CAC-40 index closed at 2,936.98, up 27.53 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
