<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Finishes Lower on Unemployment Data </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar retreated to end
mostly lower on surprisingly weak U.S. jobs data and selling ahead
of the three-day July 4 weekend. The pound surged for the fourth
straight day.
</P>
<P>
Demand for pounds began to intensify Wednesday as more
investors speculated that the Bank of England would soon raise
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The pound settled in New York at 1.6906 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6705 U.S. dollars Wednesday and up nearly 3 cents for the week.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's rate against the German currency fell to settle in
New York at 1.7535 marks, down from 1.7536 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also finished below 114 yen for the first time in a
week, settling at 113.80 yen in New York, down from 114.49.
</P>
<P>
The main force driving the dollar lower was the U.S. Labor
Department's report on June employment, which showed the jobless
rate rose to 5 percent after falling to 24-year lows of 4.8 percent
in May and 4.9 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The data provided new evidence that the U.S. economy has
slowed, further diminishing the prospects for rising interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
Other dollar rates in New York, compared with Wednesday: 1.4697
Swiss francs, down from 1.4700; 5.9055 French francs, up from
5.9040; 1,705.00 Italian lire, unchanged; 1.3730 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.3774.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
