<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes Cypriot Leaders Hold Successful Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Thursday that it hoped the talks between Greek and Turkish Cypriot
communities at the United Nations next week will lay the
groundwork for future negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Greek Cypriot President Glafcos Clarides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash will meet on July 9 for a possible settlement
of disputes between the Greek and Turkish Cypriots which has
lasted more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
"These are the first direct talks between the two Cypriot
leaders since 1994, and we want to reaffirm our very strong
support for these discussions," State Department spokesman
Nicholas Burns said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said the United States hoped the two sides would work hard
to begin a process that will bridge the differences that divide
the two communities on the island of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"The ultimate objective of this process remains a comprehensive
settlement that will establish a bi-zonal, bi-communal federation
for Cyprus," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. presidential emissary Richard Holbrooke will meet
privately and separately with the Cypriot president and the
Turkish leader prior to the discussions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970704.0247 </DOCNO>
