<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Countersigns Central African Cease-fire Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 3 (Xinhua) -- French ambassador to the Central
African Republic, Jean-Marc Simon, countersigned today in Bangui
an extended ceasefire agreement reached by the mutineers and the
inter-African peace keeping force, the MISAB, Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The six-point agreement guarantees security for the mutineers
"individually and collectively," and expects the mutineers to
withdraw with their weapons to their barracks from the Bangui
streets within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Talks will continue between the mutineers and the MISAB in the
next few days under the mediation of former Malian President
Amadou Toumani Toure on the application of the ceasefire
agreement, which also calls for the reintegration of the mutineers
into the Central African regular army.
</P>
<P>
Toure, who is president of the International Committee of
Follow-up of Bangui Accords, and General Francois Bozize, the
chief of staff of the Central African armed forces, will also
countersign the agreement on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Central African Republic experienced three mutinies within
one year by soldiers opposing President Ange-Felix Patasse.
</P>
<P>
Violent fighting broke out on June 20 and lasted for more than
one week between the mutineers and the French-backed MISAB, which
is deployed since January in Bangui.
</P>
<P>
At least 100 people were killed and 100 wounded in the fighting
which devastated many parts of Bangui and forces thousands to
flee.
</P>
<P>
France today called on the conflicting sides of the Central
African Republic to seek "national reconciliation" and to
implement "as rapidly as possible" their commitments made in the
ceasefire agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
