<HEADLINE> U.S. to Dispatch Green Berets to Africa for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States is going to
dispatch about 120 Army Green Berets to Uganda and Senegal for a
U.S.-sponsored program of training African troops in peacekeeping
and humanitarian missions, the Pentagon said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They are to leave on July 21 and stay in Africa for two months,
spokeswoman Nancy Burt told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The United States has planned to form an African force of eight
to ten battalions from seven African nations. And the troops to be
trained by the U.S. Green Berets in Uganda and Senegal are part of
that force.
</P>
<P>
The mission of the force was said to have the capacity of
responding to upheavals on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The other five African nations that are to participate in the
U.S. training program are Ethiopia, Mali, Malawi, Ghana and
Tunisia, but it is still under discussion whether and when they
will join in.
</P>
<P>
There is a problem about financing the U.S.-sponsored program
as Sen. Mitch McConnell, the chairman of the Senate appropriations
subcommittee, which controls foreign aid spending, has cut all 15
million US dollars the Clinton administration sought for the
program for 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
